product_title: Omron Body Composition Monitor with Scale - 7 Fitness Indicators & 90-Day Memory
review_body:
I was very excited to purchase the Omron Full Body Comp Scale. It appeared to be state of the art and with its 4 point of contact I was hoping for extremely, or more accurate body fat numbers. In 24 hour spans there were BODY FAT swings of 4% or more. I know from being involved in fitness that these types of swings are highly improbable, some would say impossible.

The scale also has an \\"Age\\" feature, which uses an algorithm that produces your \\"Body Age\\". As someone who trains 5 days a week and engages in a very active lifestyle my \\"Age\\" was consistently 80 years old!

I am starting to believe that our technology just is not yet available to offer a cost effective methodology of accurately measuring body fat. I have used Omron before and they get high grades in construction and durability. My hope was for a device that if not record accurate BODY FAT measurements at least record consistent records so you could gauge if you were moving in the right direction. Unfortunately that does not seem to be the case.

So there is frustration in trying to gauge my actual fitness levels using this scale - though it does appear to run a true and accurate body weight. Additionally, while the body age feature was an attractive lure for motivating me to get back to High School fitness level it would appear to have the opposite effect and rather than getting fitted for my High School Letterman Jacket had me thinking of getting fitted for dentures and depends!

review_headline: Cubital Tunnel Syndrome Sufferers Will Like This Sleeve
review_body: I am in search of the ideal elbow sleeve to relieve the pain of cubital tunnel syndrome. When the sleeves provided by my physical therapist came up short when it came to pain relief, I decided to try this sleeve. So, here goes with what I like about this sleeve: - It is sturdy. - Generous gel padding helps protect the ulnar nerve from being aggravated and causing the pain. - Sleeve fits snugly and doesn't move around on the elbow. - Sleeve fabric quickly adjusts its fit to your arm instead of forcing your arm to adjust to it. - Offered in a nice, blue color along with beige. Now for the nits to pick: - It is pricey (but what cost is too much if it does the job well?) - Make sure you select the right size! The way Bort Medical sleeves, braces, and other devices are listed in Amazon does not include a size selection from within one web page. You have sift through all of the Bort Medical items available on Amazon (17 pages of information according to my searches) to find the product you want with the size indicated in its Amazon listing title. - Develops a funky smell after one day of use. It can be hand washed, but washing it once a day and letting it air dry isn't convenient.

product_title: California Baby Hair De-tangler Spray - Calming, 8.5 Ounce
review_headline: This did help add shine and definition to my baby's hair when it was short, but it doesn't help de-tangle.
review_body:
I purchased this product last spring to help de-tangle my toddler's hair. Back then, she was only 14 months old and still had short (but curly) hair. Even then, this didn't really help us comb out the tangles in her hair. It DID help define her curls once her hair was already combed, plus it did add shine - which was nice. I followed the directions on the bottle and used this when her hair was still wet. I also tried using a conditioner first and also tried using this when her hair was dry. It still didn't help de-tangle.

Now that she's 22 months old, she has hair that goes almost down to her shoulders when it's wet. Her hair is fine and she has lots of tight Little Orphan Annie curls. With her hair now being longer, this stuff no longer does anything for it at all. In fact, I'd say that it even dries her hair out. After using this, her hair turns into a frizzy mess in a matter of hours. Her hair seriously looks better WITHOUT this product in it.

I do love that the ingredients are safe and this stuff also smells fabulous. The bottle lasts a long time. I really do wish it would work. However, I've now switched over to using California Baby Calendula Conditioner in her hair to help tame it - and that does work wonderfully - but I'm still hoping to find a natural de-tangler that actually does what it's supposed to do.

* (I use Earth Mama Angel Baby or California Baby shampoos on my baby. I use either Healthy Times or California Baby conditioner. I have very soft water and only wash my baby's hair a couple times per week. The only reason I mention this is to point out that my baby's hair care routine isn't overly harsh, so it shouldn't be making this product ineffective.)

product_title: Body Fortress Super Advanced Whey Protein, 1.95 lb. (885 g)
review_body:
I can think of several better brands then the Body Fortress brand (EAS, BSN, MuscleTech etc...) but Body Fortress is probably the best bet if you're on a budget and can't afford the high price tags of the bigger brands that are out there. Cookies N Cream is easily the best flavor for this particular brand, which isn't saying much because the rest of the flavors a completely horrid. However, to this flavors credit, it does taste a little bit like the flavor that's labeled on the container.

Despite what many people might think because of its price tag, Body Fortress is a high quality protein source and the fact that its Whey products are 52-60 grams of protein every two scoops is really impressive. The only problem that has plagued this product, is once again, the taste. This is really the only flavor from their Whey Protein Powder line that is actually somewhat easy to chug down, because the regular Chocolate, Strawberry, Vanilla and the awful Chocolate and Peanut Butter are not.

So overall, this is the only flavor that gets a passing grade from me.

review_body: I have been a fan of this drink ever since i was given a can at a motorcross in 2003 event in murray ky,i use to have to drive 40+ miles to get it so i usually bought two cases a month,in 04 i moved to galveston island texas and could not find the drink there,after a web search and much pleading i started buying direct,the shipping was high but i did not care,after about 1 1/2 years i was directed to go to Amazon to order.my first order did arrive with a coulple of empty cans due to poor packing but again i did not care,then came the day i ordered and was told the item was on backorder.not a problem as i had some reserve stock but i did quit sharing with others at the bar i managed.thinking i would get the chance to order soon but to my sadness i learned that DC brands in its infinate wisdom had discontinued the product.i contacted DC brands and was told this was true,asking if anyone had any unsold product i was told one dist. had a pallet but would not break it for case sale.as i was trying to figure out where i could come up with the money to buy a whole pallet and where i would store it if i did,the rep from DC brands e-mailed me saying the pallet had been returned and would break it for case sale.i bought all i could manage to afford (10 cases) now i see Amazon has some so i will be buying what i can get here.I can't believe that DC brands discontinued this product.how dumb is that. Dickens Cider is the best drink i have ever found if served ice cold as it recomends,i was raised drinking \\"hard cider\\" and it reminds me exactly of that.no after taste and no jitters if you don't drink more than 2 cans in 24 hours.as a club manager i put in 12-16 hr days at times,all my staff knew that at 11pm i would be comming behind the bar to get my can for the night,this allowed me to run the club till 2 am,close,oversee restocking and close out.by the time i got home at around 4 am i was able to shower and get a good nights rest.WHY WOULD DC BRANDS STOP OFFERING THIS WONDERDRINK?

product_title: Nellie's All Natural Laundry Nuggets (30 Pre-Measured Packets)
review_body:
I love Nellie's Laundry Nuggets! Several members in our family have sensitive skin and Nellie's is okay for all of us. It works well on toddler clothes as well. Surprisingly so! I've put things in the washer thinking that with liquid soap I would always pre-treat a stain. Not needed so far - all our clothes come out clean and stain free.

One user commented on the nuggets being hard. That is true for me as well. I put a nut cracker in the box of nuggets and just crunch up each nugget before I use it. It may not be a problem for machines where you add soap with the clothes. I use a front loader with a dispenser and we have had hardened chunks that did not completely dissolve. I'm able to crunch the nuggets with the nutcracker and it doesn't burst the outer pack. Just a few squeezes and the hardened nuggets are ready to use and dissolve easily with nothing leftover.

product_title: Honeywell C7189R1004 Wireless Air Indoor Sensor
review_headline: Updated review: Sometimes setup is troublesome
review_body: I ordered 4 of these for 2 thermostats, and the setup and install for the first two was a breeze. There are some limitations as to how the thermostat will use the thermostats temperature, but thats really a problem with the thermostat, not this product. However, for the other two I had problems. During setup, the unit kept giving me an orange light, when the manual only mentions either a green or red light. Even if I assumed that the orange light was supposed to mean "red," that didn't make sense. Red indicates a dead battery, and I used several fresh sets of batteries. I never could get one unit to install. I contacted Honeywell support, and since this is supposed to be a contractor installed item, they will not help. If you do purchase this item, make sure you install it immediately. That way if it doesn't work, you can just return without having to deal with honeywell support. There are reports that these units might work initially, but fail/stop connecting to thermostat in a year or so, so that is still a concern you must deal with.

review_body:
I BOUGHT THIS FLAPPER BECAUSE I WANTED TO USE THE LEAST AMOUNT OF WATER PER FLUSH. NOT ONLY DOES THAT SAVE WATER BUT IT TAKES LESS TIME FOR THE TANK TO FILL UP. IT WORKED GREAT FOR ABOUT A WEEK OR TWO AND THEN I NOTICED IT STARTED TAKING LONGER AND LONGER FOR THE TANK TO FILL UP. WHEN I TOOK THE TANK COVER OFF I NOTICED THE FLAPPER WAS STAYING UP LONGER LETTING MORE WATER OUT OF THE TANK WITH EACH FLUSH.

THERE IS A PART ON THE FLAPPER THAT YOU CAN ADJUST TO DETERMINE HOW LONG THE FLAPPER STAYS UP. BUT GRADUALLY OVER A WEEK OR TWO THIS PART SHIFTS ON IT'S OWN. UNLESS YOU ENJOY ADJUSTING YOUR TOILET FLAPPER EVERY FEW WEEKS, I WOULD AVOID THIS PRODUCT.

review_headline: These LED lights are really great, I've installed 12 of them in my garage ...
review_body:
These LED lights are really great, I've installed 12 of them in my garage and its like working in a surgical room. These emit a very clean bright light (like a clean bright florescent would be my guess, seems more like 6400K Lumens...if these are the 5000K I guess anything brighter would be like seeing the light at the end of the tunnel).

I will be buying more of these in the future for my under house storage area (approx 1700sq ft) once the current florescents start to burn out. I might also pick up another 4 pack and try using these for my spring vegetable grow starts (just to see if they work since they seem as bright as the 6400K florescents).

One thing I will caution you of is to make sure you have current tombstones that are non-shunted (tombstones are the end mounts in florescents). This will save you around $20 if you pop open your current fixtures and check, just look up on youtube about installing LED florescents and there are some pretty good video explanations.

product_title: BOND DISTRIBUTING LTD 00200 Natural Wood Stain/Sealer
review_headline: Lasted 7 years on my deck and color still good!
review_body:
Lasted 7 years on my deck and color still good! Like the other reviewer I don't get all the negative comments here. I had my handyman put this on my silvered, wearing badly deck with full, west/south sun exposure in SC 7years ago. He properly cleaned and prepped the deck and had recommended this noting the cost was worth it.

It not only turned the silvered, rough boards a lovely pale cedar color (1/2 natural + 1/2 cedar mix). It also lasted until this to year when my deck had gotten very dirty and algae'd with the SC moisture and humidity. Just got the deck power washed this week to get all dirt and grime off. It's clean now and really surprisingly the deck boards are back to the nice cedar color! Amazing as I did literally no maintenance in 7 years.

I'm now buying a couple more gallons to refresh it and re-seal again and expect another 7 years. Worth every penny just not to have to resell/stain deck every 2 years like I did in my prior home when I used Behring or Thompson stain and seals. Highly recommend this stuff!

product_title: LE 16.4ft LED Flexible Strip Lights, 300 Units SMD 3528 LEDs, 12V DC Non-waterproof, Light Strips, LED ribbon, For Garden/Home/Kitchen/Car/Bar, DIY Party Decoration Lighting
review_headline: This about sums up what you're to expect from these LEDs....
review_body:
These LED strips have their ups and downs.

It seems this is a common problem I've seen when buying these strips. The first 12v power cable interface is solid but the 2nd one (that's included in the package) seems to be either broken or on the point of breaking. Not to mention that i got my packages somewhat damaged which didn't affect the LEDs but could have caused damage with the power cables.

Remember this: These are "sticky" strips and, if you don't go over them and keep pressing them down (the first few days) they may actually come loose. And whatever you do, make sure there is NO stress where the cable is connected or it will pull loose. An alternative might be "stapling" them into place where the power cables are attached to ensure they will not come off whatever surface they are attached to.

How these units respond to very hot weather....I'm not there yet but they don't seem to lose their adhesiveness during cold weather. I'm in Alabama so summers don't get much more hot/humid here so i will update this in a few months.Still, as an alternative lighting source, i have to admit...these aren't bad.

I would guess that if someone could develop a USB connector with a wireless switching system (or just toggle switches) this could make any RV, or possibly even a man-cave look really nice.. It's all about the direction they are being used and the angles. Also, having them project onto a "white" back surface has a much nicer effect.

Oh, you might want to limit their burn period to a maximum of 16 hours, those 12v adapter get pretty HOT when the LEDs have been used for a long period of time.

And, by the way, do NOT try to run 2 strips on one 12v adapter...you will probably get a burnout in 12-18 hours. Already made that mistake in hopes of getting two for one...won't work.

I know people are planning on using these in cars but you had better make sure they are secure because, if they fall, and are kicked or dragged, they won't endure it. Tough is something these LEDs are not meant to be.ause, if they fall, and are kicked or dragged, they won't endure it. Tough is something these LEDs are not meant to be.

product_title: Frost King SP57/67 R6.7 SP56/67 Water Heater Insulation Blanket
review_headline: Total junk - didn't fit a standard 50 gallon tank
review_body:
As many others reported, this blanket, which claims it will fit around a 50 gallon tank, doesn't wrap completely around it. The tank is in a newer townhouse I bought, which I plan to move to after other work is completed inside. So, I looked it up on Amazon and as others stated, it doesn't fit many tanks and there isn't enough tape to completely seal the seam either. What's the point of not enclosing enough tape to seal the seam? Just so we have to buy a roll of some sort of tape to finish the job?

I measured the circumference of the tank before buying a blanket for it, so I thought I had the correct product. How can this company claim it fits around one when it doesn't? So I measured the width of the blanket, and yes, it's the size stated, so not sure why it doesn't fit the tank. Luckily, I bought this at a local hardware store, to which I returned it, with no hassle, but the store didn't have anything else in stock, so I left without a water heater blanket. I then tried both HDs and the Lowe's stores in my city, but the only ones they had were the same thing, or nothing on the shelves. I guess they had sold out.

Upon doing extensive research now, I've decided that a fiberglass blanket that's so thin, isn't going to be enough added insulation to make my water heater much more efficient (trying to reduce stand-by loss). So I'm looking for a thick mineral wool blanket instead. Mineral wool is both waterproof and more fireproof than this piece of junk.

Remember to insulate your water pipes as much as possible too. I know that's difficult in a finished home, but do what you can.

product_title: Lava Lite Grande 250-Ounce 27-Inch Lava Lamp
review_headline: Get ready to pull out your old records...
review_body:
It's funny how you end up doing some of the things you do...this is a perfect example. I had been given a couple of smaller Lava Lites left over from a TV commercial, and as a goof we put one on top of a subwoofer in our home theater off to the side of the screen. My wife and I would catch ourselves staring over at it on commercials or during bad TV episodes or films. So when I found out there was a BIG A** version of it I just had to one-click it on Amazon.

We have had a BALL with this thing-literally! We got the yellow and purple based on other reviews-It does have an excellent contrast of the colors, though I think it's kind of a drag not to be able to buy additional colored bottles once you have the base unit. Did I mention it is BIG?? NOT 250 ounces like the ad (That's almost 2 Gallons!)- The bottle is actually 57 ounces, so about the size of a two-liter bottle- a little wider on the bottom and and around 4\\" taller because of the cone effect of the lamp shape. Patience is a virtue here; it does take over two hours to heat up to the point where it's dripping red ball shapes. Up until that time the wildest Formaldehyde Baby, hydrogen bomb cloud, Area 51 alien, and cellulite fat looking shapes ever imagined form at all levels of the lamp-which is cool on its own! And the amount of activity once it's fully warmed up is awesome as well- it's so big inside that seeing 6, 10, or more balls dripping while large ghost shapes are behind is common. As other reviews have said, make sure you center the lamp-another advantage is with this size one being so tall the actual bulb for the lamp is far enough off the base that you don't need to worry as much about heat damaging veneers underneath. We keep it on a black Paridigm sub for six hours with no signs of damage, but you're on your own here for your use. And the sub if if anything seems to help the experience. And we heeded the advise of another good reviewer and we do limit the total time to six hours, not the eight the one-sheet that comes with it says.

Over a month now, and running 2-3 days a week, it's been fantastic. This is a blatant trick by Amazon to make me go buy SACD's of Dark Side of the Moon, Goodbye Yellow Brick Road, and a few other classic 70's LP's... and it WORKED! A great talking point, stress reliever, and reason to get slightly altered and turn up the volume. Highly Recommended!

product_title: Suncourt Flush Fit Register Air Booster Fan and Flush Fit Mount Adaptor
review_body:
I have a wall heater vent that is about 40 feet from the furnace. The contractor that put in the bedroom addition decided to connect the duct to the end of a duct that already feeds two other rooms. In the past, I had to close the other two vents in order to feel any appreciable flow out of the end vent, and still the room was much colder than the rest of the house.

Although this model is described as white in color, the booster that I received is closer in color to the gray outlet- and switch plates. As others have mentioned, it is somewhat loud, and removing the inner grates helped to some extent. On closer inspection, I found that one of the fans would not spin freely. I discovered that both fans were not assembled correctly. Specifically, the fan bearings were not pressed fully into the hub. When I looked at the gap between the fan (the rotating part) and the frame, I could see the coils of copper wire inside. Supporting the hub, I pressed each fan down until it seated fully. The blades sit much closer to the hub support arms. I noticed that both fans spin much more freely and the booster is noticeably quieter.

The fans are model DFC902512M by coolingfan.cn, 12VDC, 0.20A. This model is not listed on their website, but a similar 92x92x25mm, 12VDC, 0.20A model listed has the following specifications: voltage: 6-13.8VDC, speed: 2500rpm, airflow: 48.1cfm, pressure: 2.60mmH2O, noise: 31dBa, weight: 77g. Tach measurements give the following fan speeds: low: 2000rpm, medium: 2200rpm, high: 2500rpm. At medium speed, the noise level seems comparable to that of the unboosted vents closer to my furnace. There is a more significant jump in speed and noise from medium to high than low to medium. I use medium.

While the unit was open, I also desoldered the thermistor from the control board and extended it with a pair of wires by about 8 inches out the back. I was able to thread the two thin wires through the original hole for the thermistor and out of one of the rectangular access holes for the fan catches without the need for drilling an additional hole. The thermistor now sits deeper inside the duct. The unit no longer cycles on and off repeatedly at the start and end of the heater cycle due to the fan blowing directly on the thermistor. There is no hysteresis programmed into the controller, so the fans cycle on and off at exactly the set temperature.

The LEDs for the indicator panel fit into tubular guides. You can inserted a small wad of cotton or tissue into each tube to dampen the amount of light emitted, and not alter the external appearance of the booster.

The booster comes with a 12VDC, 500ma transformer-type wall wart. According to my Kill-a-Watt meter, it is drawing 1W at idle, 5W on low, 6W on medium, and 7W on high. Note that the fans are rated 2.4W each according to the labels, 4.8W together. When power is reset, the booster seems to remember the last-used settings.

This booster fits best if the duct opening is flat and square. In my case, the metal duct extends slightly from the drywall and the spackling is uneven. Due to this protrusion and the design of the plastic faceplate and adapter, the unit does not sit flush against the surrounding drywall. I will have to either trim the duct and spackling flush with the drywall, or adhere a strip of thin foam insulation around the perimeter of the back of the faceplate to close this irregular gap.

The room is warmer and comfortable with the booster installed and running. Considering the quality of parts and type of materials used, I do wish it was a little less expensive. I also had to order the adapter plate for larger vents, plus a 120VAC flat-plug extension cord so that it can be plugged into a wall outlet behind furniture. However, it is relatively simple device that can be completely disassembled and is servicable to the circuit board level with readily-available parts.

product_title: Nordic Pure 20x20x2M13-3 20x20x2 MERV 13 Pleated AC Furnace Air Filter, Box of 3, 2-Inch
review_body:
It's always somewhat surprising to pull out an old furnace filter and see how much dust it has collected over a few months. My particular system uses a 2" x 20" x 20" filter -- a size that is not readily available from the "big box" home centers. This proved to be a blessing in disguise, as it caused me to research what "MERV" meant -- and I discovered that the filters carried by local vendors were of rather low quality in the level of filtration. As an allergy sufferer, I was pleased to be able to purchase a higher level of filtration that should reduce the allergens moving though my home's air handling system. These filters appear to fulfill my needs very well and were quite reasonably priced.

In my home, the furnace is in the attic, and the filter is positioned just behind a grill in the ceiling of a central hall. The measurements of filters tend to be slightly less than the nominal measurement, which made installation a 'three hand' situation. (Solved by turning on the system fan, allowing the air flow to hold the filter in place while closing the grill that holds the filter in place.) The filter does not firmly contact the sides of the filter box, but the duct behind the filter is slightly smaller, so that in operation, the air pressure holds the filter against the duct giving an adequate seal.

The filter appears to be sturdy and should preform its task without structure failure.

review_body:

When I upgraded to Version 10, I had difficulties restoring my databases. This is not the fault of Cook'n, rather my own lack of diligence with backing up data appropriately. I have to start from scratch AGAIN with my Cook'n. Some recipes are lost forever I feel but maybe I have learnt with time to make appropriate backups.

Getting back to the program, it can be as simple or as complicated as you like. I do not use menus or indeed shopping lists most of the time but I still come back to Cook'n for its ease of use and flexibility.

The only beef I have with Cook'n is the printing side of things. As I am in Australia, paper sizes are not the same as the US but with a little tweaking, I can get around that. More printing options would be nice but that's on the wishlist.

I must say that DVO's customer service is great. I lost my purchased cookbooks but the DVO team were able to resend me what ones they could considering that I purchased them over 4 years ago. What book they couldn't send me, they offered a free download of any book I liked. All this done in a matter of 2 short days and only a couple of emails. Thanks Ryan, you are a legend and a lifesaver.

product_title: Adobe Premiere Elements 10
review_headline: Does NOT Make HD Movies for Legacy Players
review_body:
I have used five generations of Adobe Premiere, all the way back to version 1.5. While it is still a good editor with some strong features, the latest version, PE 10 flagrantly misrepresents its capability. It states on the box \\"Burn Blu-ray quality HD movies using standard DVD discs and burners.\\" This statement is under the heading \\"Share videos...with friends wherever they are\\". The problem is that your friends will have to buy a new \\"1080 HD DVD Player\\" in order to take advantage of this feature. Adobe does not specify that their new feature requires new hardware and therefore it is misleading and caused me to waste a good deal of time trying to find an explanation on their website. Not to mention that the claim that it works with any HD video camera is simply not true. It worked with my older camcorders, but not my new Sony.
On the other hand, the software does a fine job of basic editing and is particularly good at rendering discs because it has good control over the menu text and icon placement and has an excellent DVD preview screen so you don't have to burn DVDs to know if your menus launch the scenes correctly. Rendering to all formats is impressively fast and the Win 7 64 bit implementation is robust and only crashes occasionally.
More problems with PE are caused by Adobe's strategy to attempt to persuade users to use this product as the nexus of all their stored video and still media. Anybody who is serious about video editing will have a host of programs including viewers, converters and other editors. PE's cumbersome attempt to grab all the media files results in screens popping up unexpectedly that take you out of the core editing experience. This was never the case in the older products. Bad product direction for serious video editors. Also bothersome are their frequent attempts to pull users into using the related suite of Photoshop products, no doubt because they are losing market share to Picasa and other free photo editing programs.
This product is now no better than the Cyberlink competitor and the only reason I remain an Adobe user is that I am familiar with their menus.

product_title: Poser Pro [OLD VERSION]
review_headline: Quality OK for Freeware, but not for a $500 Product!
review_body: Review of Smith Micro's Poser Pro Well, at this juncture I've been working almost daily with this product, and thought it was high time I shared some of my impressions with other prospective customers/victims. First of all, as a long-time software professional, I am quite aware of the complexities associated with 3D rendering, and the high demand on processing resources -- both memory and CPU. Even though I'm running a fairly capable machine (quad-core, 64-bit, 8Gig of ram, 2 - 1-terrabyte drives, Win XP-64, etc.), I am prepared to accept that complex 3D scene rendering will take some time. That said, what I DO NOT accept is the necessity for the program to outright refuse to render, or even LOAD some scenes, reporting \\"not enough memory to load texture map'! In software engineering terminology, this just indicates sloppy memory management. Even after researching the issues, tweaking the render settings, running a 3rd-party memory management utility -- the problem persists. Perhaps even harder to excuse is the generally brittle nature of the package. It regularly becomes necessary to resort to ctl-alt-del, bring up the program manager, find the process, and use the \\"kill process tree\\" command to get rid of the hung application, and then start the whole process over from the start, often losing work in the process. Then, of course, there are the incessant \\"An unexpected exception occurred: -50\\" messages. Once again, ctrl-alt-del, etc., is the only way to proceed. Don't even bother looking in the event manager, or searching for a log that might explain the source of the problem. The Poser \\"engineers\\" apparently considered such niceties as superfluous. Interestingly, it's often possible (and necessary) to load a scene that Poser Pro refuses to accept by using Poser 7! I can then eliminate some elements, save the file, and reload back into Poser Pro. Did someone decide it was necessary to introduce some additional bugs into the flagship package.? Ialso have a strong suspicion that the program suffers from some severe memory leaks. If you monitor memory usage, you'll see that, regardless of the nature of the scene, memory usage just keeps on increasing, until, inevitably -- that's right: ctrl-alt-del. The thing that amazes me most, is the proliferation of gushing reviews of this shoddy piece of . . . programming. Are the reviewers on Smith Micro's payroll? Have they done any more with it than render a quick naked woman, gawk over it, and then write: \\"WOW, what a GREAT product!\\"? There are, of course, so many other annoying quirks as to defy enumeration here. Suffice it to say, that this is an extremely irritating program with which to work. Smith Micro touts this as a \\"professional package,\\" an utterly absurd assertion. It's quality is such that I might overlook the bugs in a freeware package, but certainly not in something costing nearly five-hundred bucks. Oh well, there's a sucker born every minute. Now, as someone who has watched my own company's profits eroded by software piracy, I am generally opposed to such abuses, however, in cases like this, my advice is to acquire the product from someplace like Emule, or Vuse, or other torrent servers, use it for a while, and if you still think it's worth the asking price, then by all means, write that check. Otherwise, just use it at a cost that's precisely what it's worth: $0.

product_title: Power PDF Standard, Bilingual English/French
review_headline: Less Bloated Acrobat Replacement, but Quirks
review_body:
I've used Nuance Paperport pro V12 and the bundled PDF program for a while on an older XP computer (soon to be retired).

Power PDF is a significant step up that adds form creation, OCR features, conversion to/from PDF from lots of document formats, and adds a version of Dragon for adding notes to PDF's. It is at it's heart a PDF converter.

Installation was completely uneventful. The registration/activation is a bit annoying but it seems the sort of the way the software world is headed. This hasn't always been the case for Nuance products. Paperport in particular was known for installation problems.

Like most Nuance products I've used this has a quirkyness to its interface. If you have used other Nuance programs you'll know what I mean. If not you'll either get used to it or become frustrated. I think most people adapt without much trouble.

In general I've used the PDF conversion features and some basic form creation so far. I've played a little with the dragon notes and it seems to work pretty well with my voice.

The results seem to open on fine on Acrobat Reader XI and Acrobat Pro X..

Power PDF installed and worked well. It has a broad set of features. The interface is Nuance "quirky" and the registration/activation is a bit annoying. So I'm giving 4 stars to Power PDF.

Hope this helps someone.

product_title: Quicken Home & Business 2013
review_headline: Don't do it!!! Wait for the bug revisions - R11 still not it.
review_body:
I admit it, I got excited for the new version and upgraded. Nearly all the marketing features hyped above are not ready for prime time. Budgeting is a big fail. I'm going to revert to an excel spreadsheet and manually transfer the values. The numbers are off and there is an odd way of handling categories and future transactions.

Mobile sync crashes around 50% of the time and takes roughly 5 minutes to complete, while the software is locked and unusable. I hit sync and walk away. Using the iOS interface took some getting used to, and I may use it \\"on the fly\\" but it's not as nimble as the Pocket Quicken app in the days of Palm (yes, I'm that old and have been using Quicken that long!)

I could go on, but the other reviews hit the high points. I came from 2011 and wish that I could go back, but I've put too much new info in the data file, so I'm stuck.

If I could do it all over again, I'd wait to upgrade until users report all the kinks are worked out (if ever). Just head over to the forums and see what people are posting. I wish I did before I purchased. As of today (10/8/12) I have taken a step backward from usage. Thank god for Excel to fill in the holes while other people that purchased this too early \\"beta test\\" for Intuit.

---------------------------------------
EDIT 11/15/12: I just downloaded the seventh (R7) update and it completely corrupted my data. Mind you, I had to add a \\"balancer\\" transaction to a few of my accounts with the upgrade to 2013. Amounts were off, but I couldn't figure out where or why.

With R7, I had to restore from a backup (thank God I backup). If I could downgrade this review to zero stars I would. I no longer attempt to use the budgeting feature, we use excel and manually patch the data back into Quicken. I have mobile completely disabled (it added corrupt data). I bought a book to understand some of the \\"new features,\\" if only to find a workaround.

If I could go back to my previous version or if there was a reasonable competitor I would abandon this product immediately.

--------------
EDIT 3/2/2013
--------------

We're on R11 (patch 11) now. I'm happy to report that I haven't had any data corruptions recently--for a couple of months. The mobile/iOS experience is still not working. Now every time I try to use it recently I get a \\"Data Error\\" and it boots me completely out. That is to say it requires that I go back an re-enter my UN and PW as opposed to simply the iOS program PIN. Then it simply gives the same error and requires a sign out. I may delete the account and create a new one, again, to see if that fixes it as it has in the past. As you can gather from my review above and other users, it hasn't been sufficiently reliable for me to consistently use it, so I can't say it's a huge loss for me. However, if you view it as a big selling point, don't purchase this software for this feature.

There are many bugs that are still not worked out (again, venture over to Quicken's support forum). My view on the software is still the same. This is not an adequately vetted program and is still not ready for public release. If you MUST upgrade for some reason, such as banking compatibility, it's tolerable--at least you won't lose data (well, maybe). I still backup frequently. The only reason I'd say that's a remotely acceptable option is because there are no real competitors here. My rating stands at 1 of 5 stars.

review_headline: Will Not Work on My Windows 7 Computer
review_body:
I installed this today and after a few hours, tons of searching for a solution online, and plenty of messing with my computer settings, I am throwing the towel in. I continually get an error message that the "Sound Level is Too Low" and I cannot even get past the profile setup wizard due to this error. A user forum I was reading mentioned that if you call Nuance with this problem they will spend plenty of time making sure you checked all the obvious solutions, then they apologize and tell you they have a software glitch they are working on. I haven't subjected myself to this process, and I don't plan on it, either. No product should require this much work just to get it to function adequately.

Well, a glitch working with Windows 7 is a big deal. I am computer savvy, I can build a PC from parts, I can install software, I can change system settings in Control Panel, and I can troubleshoot simple problems better than most computer users. I checked every single listed solution I was able to try, and I simply cannot get this software to run properly. If this is a known bug, as it seems to be, then this product should not be sold as compliant with Windows 7. I am returning this, there is no way I plan on spending even more time and effort getting this to work. I checked the microphone function with the Windows Sound Recorder, and while it is a bit low, it records just fine. So, either the issue is the included headset (hopefully Nuance is not hair-brained enough to send out a faulty headset that will make their software look like garbage) -or- the problem is that their software is buggy and doesn't run properly on my new, clean, non-buggy computer.

product_title: Autodesk Sketchbook Pro 2011
review_headline: Easy to use somewhat powerful paint program that will help turn you into a pretty good digital artist if u are not already one
review_body:
I loved this product. It's a paint/photo program, not a drawing program. Adobe Photoshop (AP) is a paint/photo program; Adobe Illustrator (AI) is a drawing program. AP creates bitmap files, and AI create vector files. Bitmap files are images made up of little dots. Whereas vector files are mathematical formulas that are easily scaleable. The native files for Sketchbook are stored in layered TIF format, but they can be exported in many different bitmap file formats: gif, jpeg, and PSD.

I have used quite a number of different kinds of computer applications over the years: wordprocessing, spreadsheet, presentations, database, email, WYSIWYG Web page designers, paint/photo, and drawing. Of all these different types of computer programs I have had the most difficulty learning to use well the paint/photo kind. This is probably because I am not really an artist - at least not one adept at creating visual pictures using my hands. I am much better at taking photos with a digital camera and tweeking them using Adobe Photoshop. I have always found AP to be a tough cookie when it comes to creating original artwork from scratch.

Sketchbook Pro makes it much easier for me to create original artwork from scratch. It is designed to be used with a digital pen tablet. The intuitive user interface is slick and pleasing to eye, and you will be up and running in no time using pencils, brushes, layering, and pan/zoom features. This product is going to make it easy for you to \\"sketch\\" out a rough draft of the artwork you want to create. It will not create a masterpiece probably, but you can certainly move your file into AP and tweek your art to your heart's content.

This product was easy for me to install, and it has never appeared sluggish to me when using it. I suppose the only problem I had with the product is its name. I think of the word \\"sketch\\" as being a drawing. Thus at first I thought this was a drawing program. So don't be confused by the name. What you will get with this product is an easy to use somewhat powerful paint/photo program that will help turn you into a pretty good digital artist if you are not already one. And if you are already expert I suspect you will thoroughly enjoy this product to create the early-goings of a paint file you will fine tune in AP. 5 stars!this product is an easy to use somewhat powerful paint/photo program that will help turn you into a pretty good digital artist if you are not already one. And if you are already expert I suspect you will thoroughly enjoy this product to create the early-goings of a paint file you will fine tune in AP. 5 stars!

product_title: Mac OS X 10.1 [OLD VERSION]

Mac OS 10.1, the long-awaited gift from Apple, is impressively stable. The stability of this OS gives it an edge over the older build of Mac OS 9 (and older systems). Dynamic memory allocation and preemptive multitasking are positive aspects too.
However, I would not suggest OS X on a G3 unless you are ready for slow resizing and tediously long launch times.
Indeed, even though it is slower, I feel that I am obliged to use OS X on my 600 MHz iBook - not because Apple is phasing out "classic" support. The only thing that truly binds me to OS X is that it is much more stable than OS 9. However, seeing how good things are coming with the new ideas from Apple as they update the system, I would suggest keeping an eye open. Perhaps OS X will speed up soon.

To make matters worse, we have no idea which keys are install on which machines. I guess Abode expects you to track this, but I can't figure out how to retrieve the installed keys. This is a business, I don't know what the guy before me did. So, now we get to call Adobe everytime we need to use one of our licenses and they do not have the greatest support team. This has cost us plenty in productivity and the product isn't cheap to begin with. If you can avoid using this product I would recommend doing so.

review_headline: Wonderful tool to assist you on your way
review_body: I don't believe this is for sale anymore on Amazon (although you can buy from DietPower directly) however I first discovered this software by looking on Amazon. I'm so happy I did! I started a \\"diet\\" a month before I discovered this and was putting in a lot of exercise and moderately watching what I ate but not getting great results. I had lost a couple pounds but nothing near where I should have been for as much hard work as I was putting into exercise and strength training. I went to the DietPower website and downloaded a two week trial version for free. In those two weeks I lost five pounds simply because I had visibility to the calories I was taking in and what I was burning off through exercise. The software itself is rather complex but it is very simple to use. Logging foods and exercise is very easy and quick. It even helps you track your water intake based on demands from food and exercise. It helps track the nutrition in what you are eating so you have visibility to how much vitamins you intake and where you might be lacking throughout the day. This is great software. I would highly encourage anyone, even those maintaining weight, to go grab a trial version of this and try it out. This software has shown me that I can eat well and still achieve results.

product_title: Norton 360 5.0 Sop 10 User
review_body:
Norton doesn't work and you will be expected to pay $99 to get Customer Support when the program fails. I am very computer literate and relied on Norton to protect my computer from viruses and malware. I am quite competent at avoiding threats, but there are some that even the most experienced user can't prevent. Their program did not catch an old \\"virus\\" (technically malware) that has been out for a long time, so it wasn't an unavoidable problem.

When I contacted customer support for help removing the program Norton didn't catch, they tried to charge me $99 to correct their mistake before they would even discuss the problem (either do it yourself or pay $99). I spent over 4 hours working with inexperienced techs that did not have adequate computer knowledge trying to get the problem fixed. The \\"Customer Service\\" agent deleted at least one unrelated program from my computer (was not infected) that I will have to pay to replace. I will now have to spend my time trying to figure out how to totally remove the malware from my computer as it seems to be in the registry and affecting my computer after Norton's software claimed it was quarantined (it took 4 hours and 3 techs to even get that far on top of the multiple scans I had run). I will likely have to pay someone to work on my computer to ensure that my computer is safe and pay for new antivirus software. My computer is nearly unusable.

Bottom line, Windows 7 has great antivirus software built in (you do have to find it and turn it on) or you can use a number of free options that work as well or better than Norton. It has been years since I've tried Mcafee so I can't comment on it's effectiveness. Do not depend on Norton even if you are computer literate. If you aren't knowledgeable about the latest threats or if other family members that aren't use it, you DEFINITELY don't want to rely on Norton.

PERRLA was recommended by three coworkers who had receintly graduated from college. PERRLA is amazing. I have completed my first semester without even one APA error. It makes paper writing a breeze. Step by step instruction for every paper. PERRLA saves all citations so previously used sources do not have to be re-cited. Saves hours of time for each paper. product_title: ACT! 2005 [Old Version]
review_body:
My problems began with installation.

1.) File was corrupted upon loading the software from the CD. Went to ACT website, they had the file available (not a unique problem, obviously), and I was then able to load.

2.) I then had problems converting data from ACT! 6.0. Went to ACT website again, only solution was to uninstall and reinstall. I also shut down Spybot, which may have corrupted the first loading. They tell you to shut down Anti-Virus software, which I did, but not Spybot. Data converted after doing this.

3.) I have NO custom fields, but data from my Salutation field did not convert. All fields blank. Since I had converted to ACT! 6.0 from a previous customer manager, this meant I lost all my contact first names, and this was the deal-breaker. I may have been able to get through this, but see 4.).

4.) I did not notice item three for several hours, and used the program during that time. As previous reviewers have noted, it is noticably slower than ACT! 6.0. It also slows down the rest of one's computer, reboot is slower, etc. I also started having problems with MS Outlook crashing, which had never happened before.

All things considered, I decided to return the software, and stick with ACT! 6.0, at least for a year or so while they figure things out. ACT chose to go with a more complex platform, which may help them with their corporate accounts, but is more problematic for smaller users. Computer speed will continue to be an issue. Also, you cannot synch with other users with Windows XP any longer. You must upgrade to Windows Professional.

I found ACT! (Best Software) to be good about trying to make things work, and allowing me to return the software. Their support group surpasses their product development group. If you are dying to try ACT! 2005, either wait a few months while they fix a few things, or be prepared for a tedious conversion process and slowerperformance. Buy from Amazon or Best Software or a reputable vendor directly, so you can return the software if necessary.

product_title: Chess Tactics ART 3.0
review_body:
In this review, I consider 3 points

1) organization and difficulty of the material
2) interface
3) software vs book (M. Block \\"The art of combination in chess\\")

1) The soft is marketed to players with elo up to 2300. At the same time, the material is classified according to tactical and geometric motives. This has both pros and cons, and IMHO suits better to beginners and lower itermediates rather than to more advanced intermediates and experts. A book cannot be organized both ways; a software certainly makes it possible, but no such feature (e.g. @show a random position with a difficulty between 50 to 120) exists in CT-ART (even in the test mode, the topic is still shown in the upper bar).

The difficulty varies dramatically throughout the course. Comparing with well known Konotop series of tests in chess tactics, difficulty level of 10 should belong to \\"test for beginners\\" (ca 800-1200 elo), while problems with difficulty above 110 would probably be found in \\"tests for candidate masters\\" (2000 FIDE Elo and above).

2) interface: fair to poor. First of all, if you have windows Vista you need to know a thing or two about the interactions of this soft with your OS. Convecta recommends turning the UCA off, which is plain ridiculous, because ct-art also works fine (if it ever works fine) when you install it in a separate folder outside your \\"program files\\" folder. Secondly, I never succeeded in making the pieces move faster and the intervals shorter (the pieces move extremely slow. If the problem is easy I nearly fall asleep). Theoretically you can control the speed and the interval, but in practice the soft doesnt respond: thisngs move the same slow way whatever speed you set. If you make a mistake, the program displays a refutation if it typed in. Otherwise, it shows a \\"prompt\\" using ridiculous blinking markers. I had to quit the excersise and restart it each time I made a mistake. You CAN turn them off though, this option does work.

3) CT-ART vs Bloch's book. What is good in CT-ART? The very selection of the problems. I do find it excellent, it teaches precision and consideration of all tactical motives in each position. But: here the soft and the book are nearly identical. What is bad in CT-ART? Basically, everything else. Poor interface. ridiculous ratings that have nothing to do with the reality. In many positions there are several ways to win, but the program gives you a penalty (tipically, the first move is unique, but on later stages.... Once I got a penalty for correctly executed checkmate in one!). On the other hand, when solving a difficult problem (90+) I happened to fail to find the principle ideas, but still collect 60% of points for that problem! Conclusion: I quit the soft and got the book.

UDP: Now CT-ART is already available with the new Peshk@ interface. As far as I was told, the interface issues have been resolved.

Hope this hepls.

review_body: Ditto to everything "arryman" said below. I am an Art Director and I recently upgraded from version 3. review_body:

When we requested a fix from Intuit, the reponse from The Office of the President at Intuit was, \\"Sure it's a bug, but Quicken is sold AS IS with NO WARRANTY. product_title: BackUp MyPC
review_headline: BackUp My Pc is everything it is advertised to be........
review_body:
I was looking for a back up program that would work with Windows XP Home. I did my homework by searching and checking out all the available back up programs on the internet. I also checked to see if my RW and CD and ScanDisk drivers were listed in the compatable drive section of their website. After having downloaded a trial copy from Stomp website I found that it worked perfectly with my computer and system. I then ordered the software from Amazon.com and it works just great. No trouble downloading and preforming a complete back up of my hard drive. I backed up 11.3 GB in 4 hrs. and 30 minutes which took 17 cd's for the 87,393 files. This time also included the formating of the CD's and the verifying of the data. Not a single error.
I can recommend it highly that is if your cdrw and hard drive and other drives are compatable.
Tom McCallie

product_title: Mac OS X Snow Leopard Family Pack (5-User)
review_headline: Snow Leopard is NOT ready for prime-time. Do NOT upgrade!
review_body: In short: Snow Leopard (SL) feels like a Beta release. It is NOT ready for prime-time. This honestly feels like the release of Microsoft Me (Millenium edition, remember when MS put out that garbage as an \\"upgrade\\" to '98?). SL is THAT bad. Details: With every update to OS X you hear the stories of third-party apps not being compatible and causing issues. Understandable, given the limitations of some (especially smaller) developers. In my case, the apps in question are Apple's own Mail and iTunes. Specifically, Mail would lock while trying to download new mail. The update circle/arrow next to each email address would spin all day. Meanwhile, the same mail came through just fine on my wife's MacBook Pro (running 10.5.8). iTunes would at some point (while sitting idle all day while I'm off at work) inform me that my iTunes library could not be found and the pop-up error messages (one for each of the thousands of items in my iTunes library) could not be Force Quit. After rebooting, everything would work fine for a while. This is why I switched to a Mac. To avoid this exact issue (rebooting multiple times a day just to do the basics). I upgraded my iMac (just over a year old, Intel Core 2 Duo 2.4) to SL on 9/3 and gave it a week to sort out any issues. Last night I threw in the towel and reverted back to Leopard (this is why you MUST create a cloned copy of your hard drive before you upgrade (use Super Duper or Carbon Copy Cloner and create a bootable drive (and test it! (hold down the Option key while you reboot)) before you do any OS upgrade (PC or Mac))). Time Machine couldn't save me. It told me I was out of disk space (I wasn't). I know all the great features Apple put into SL (which I why I upgraded so early in the life-cycle) and was loving them (smart disk eject, click and hold on an app in the Dock and see all the occurences of that app, super fast boot times, etc). But until the bugs get fixed, I don't dare go near Microsoft Me - sorry,I meant Snow Leopard - again. Apple, shame on you for putting out this garbage as a gold master. You were a month ahead of schedule and still rushed the QA. And it shows. No longer will I be able to say \\"get a Mac, it just works\\". I've put many friends into Macs over the years. Now I just can't recommend them without a huge caveat. Not until Apple makes this right. Well, Apple... we're waiting....

product_title: Fluenz French 1+2+3+4+5 for Mac, PC, iPhone, iPad & Android Phones, Version 3
review_body:
I have a general working knowledge of several languages - studied in high school and college and through living and working in various countries - but have never formally studied French and knew very little of it. I've been looking for years for a suitable program for it but have always shied away from the \\"total immersion\\" approach of Rosetta Stone. From my, albeit limited, exposure to Rosetta, it seems that their lessons leave too many unsolved questions about what's going on. To follow them, you'd really need to equip yourself with a grammar book and dictionary and be prepared to dig for lots of explanations the lessons don't supply.

The theory behind an immersion program seems to be that little children learn languages much better than adults, so we should try to mimic that experience with adults. The trouble is that adults don't learn as little children do - and as the Fluenz creators recognize, that's both a plus and a minus. It's a disadvantage in that adults will most likely never master a language quite as deeply as a child. An English-speaking adult who learns French, for example,will never be able to speak French without at least a trace of an English accent. But having learned English thoroughly before learning French is also a huge advantage! English speaking adults can leverage their existing knowledge of how a language (English) works to learn the target language. As adult English speakers, we already understand the many forms we need a verb to take: for I, you, s/he, we, they. So when we learn the \\"I\\" form, we look for the \\"he\\" form and etc. Because of the knowledge we have of what we don't know, we make much more rapid progress in the target language than a child could.

But. We can do so only if we are given explanations that correspond to the questions we naturally have. For a simple example: we naturally wonder, why do you say you are going \\"en France\\" but \\"a Paris\\"? It's unnecessarily frustrating if the language program youuse never bothers to provide you with the simple explanation that you always use \\"a\\" when you are going to a city but not necessarily to a country.

Each Fluenz lesson begins with a short intro, then goes to a dialogue which provides information and vocabulary relevant to tourists. Each lesson develops and expands upon the grammar introduced in the previous lessons. Because most people traveling to Francophone countries will be interested in getting the basics down, lessons often center on being in a cafe and ordering food, or with traveling from place to place or asking questions at a hotel. These short dialogues can be listened to with no subtitles, with subtitles only in French, and with subtitles in English and French. After the student has listened to the dialogue, the instructor comes on and goes through what the student has just heard, line by line, adding additional relevant information as well as mnemonic devices to help students retain the information. The instructor also adds related concepts or structures to those introduced in the dialogue. Subsequent \\"workouts\\" encourage students to practice through reading, writing, listening and speaking. What I find particularly delightful are the little comments the instructor sprinkles in along the way about some element from film or sports or culture. Once, the instructor mentioned that the bidet was \\"one of France's great gifts to womankind.\\" I doubt I'll ever forget that line as it was so unexpected and human a remark.

As much as I love this program, I would have given it 4.75 stars rather than 5 if that were possible because the software is just a bit glitchy. You have to play around with it in order to get it to work properly. For example, you might, in a given workout, get just one question and find, when you hit \\"next\\" that the workout seems to be done. There is no way to move forward within it. What you need to do in that case is select \\"next workout\\" and then go back - and backwards -until you complete the previous workout. It took a while for me to realize this, so I missed some valuable practice along the way.

Overall, Fluenz is an excellent program, long overdue. I look forward to learning my next language with Fluenz.

product_title: The Invincible Iron Man: The Complete Collection
review_headline: Amazing value at the original price
review_body:
This collection consists of actual comic books that have been individually scanned and converted to PDF files. This is one of a number of such collections, all of which were an absolutely amazing value when they were first published, with hundreds of comic books, some dating back to the 1960s, available on a single DVD for one low price. Unfortunately, Marvel Comics refused to continue licensing their content to Git Corp and the collections are no longer available. Today, the DVDs are collector's items, sometimes going for hundreds of dollars. At their original publishing price, this was an incredible deal. At the prices today, when you can even find them, you should definitely think twice.

The files are not DRM (Digital Rights Management) protected, so you can copy the PDF files to your computer or laptop, even to your Kindle Fire tablet. You can also create backup DVDs to make sure that your collection always remains accessible. If you view the collections on your computer or laptop, using the Adobe official PDF viewer, everything is fine. If you view the collections on your Kindle Fire tablet, there is a semi-transparent "Marvel" watermark that will show up on every page. I've tried every PDF viewer in the Amazon App Store, including the Adobe PDF app, and they all exhibit this flaw. Once I got used to it, though, it didn't bother me much and it's handy to have a really portable way to read these files.

Each file contains one complete comic book, including the front and back covers, all of the advertisements, the letters page, and so on. The files are arranged in two-page spreads, 1100 pixels wide by 850 pixels high. I can reduce these to roughly 75% of full size and still read them. Much below that and the text becomes hard to read and the details are muddy.

For the collections that go back to the 60s and 70s, it's both nostalgic and hilarious to read some of the advertisements (Sea Monkeys! X-Ray Specs! Charles Atlas!). The scan quality in those earlier issues is surprisingly good, considering the age of each comic book. These are very readable, in very good condition.

This collection begins in 1963 with Tales of Suspense #39 (for 12 cents!) where Iron Man was first introduced. In 1964, in Tales of Suspense #59, Captain America joined Iron Man and the comic title officially became Tales of Suspense featuring Iron Man and Captain America. This continued until 1968, where issue #99 became the final Tales of Suspense issue and each hero subsequently got his own title. The Iron Man title continued through issue 332, in 1996, after which Marvel rebooted the character and restarted the issue numbering. The reboot concluded in 1997 with issue #13, with a second reboot beginning in 1998 and ending in 2004 with issue #89. There was a third reboot in 2005 and the collection concludes with issue #12 of that reboot, in 2006. In addition, the collection contains Annuals 1 through 15, Annuals 1998 through 2001, Giant-Size Iron Man #1 (from 1975), and a detailed Iron Man bio. All told, counting index files, there are 586 files to browse.The scan quality in those earlier issues is surprisingly good, considering the age of each comic book. These are very readable, in very good condition.

product_title: TurboTax Basic 2003
review_body: I was hesitant to buy Turbo this year after having left to buy TaxCut last year when Intuit had the arrogance to put spyware into their product and add a disturbing activation process. I had always been a Turbo user but was so incensed at last years shenanigans by Intuit that I switched to TaxCut (and would do so again, should they initiate the same nonsense as they did in 2002). In any case, TaxCut in not even remotely as user friendly or robust as Turbo and given the opportunity to have Turbo as it was in 2001 and prior I have gladly come back. After reading the reviews on Amazon I hesitated, but am glad I gave it a try. The installation (on a Win 98 machine)was flawless (except for a minor glitch of it crashing my system when updating the software the first time). Useability is as good as always, in my opinion, which as I've said is light years ahead of TaxCut. In light of the options available on the market, Turbo is the clear choice (unless you want to suffer with a lesser product like TaxCut -- which I will grudgingly do again if Intuit plays games like they did in 2002!)

product_title: Microsoft Windows 7 Home Premium Upgrade Family Pack (3-User) [Old Version]
review_body:
Great price on an awesome OS. When installing on your second and 3rd PC make sure to answer and you call the MS helpline make sure to answer no to installed on multiple PC's and talk to the MS rep, let them know your using the family pack and you should be good to go. I cant say enough good things about Windows 7. Using it on 3 PC's, networking and security is a breeze using home group and related permissions. Can use media center for free OTA DVR recording, and share out recorded TV and family videos for the whole house. I have done a ton of Win7 Installs for friends and family and the great majority of hardware is detected right off the bat. Occasionally you may need to tweak a setting but by far this is the best MS OS to date. Its fun to use and easy to manage and works with alot of software. Pro edition adds Domain logons and XP mode, however most shouldnt need these features and can still use MS Virtual PC or VMware for similar functionality. Media Center is fun to tweak, if you do this with a 15 IR remote you can use your PC isntead of Tivio or other similar PVR/DVR solutions. For most this will save 60-80$ a month on TV costs and when coupled with netflix and Hulu offers up some great programming. We get 60 stations in my city over the air which is more than enough. My kids havent complained one bit and have many new programs they love to watch on PBS and Qubo.

Detection of network devices and hardware is a snap. Any Dual core 2Ghz plus machine with 2GB ram runs great, but for the record I have even tested on a 5yr old Latitude D610 with 1.5GB ram and even that system runs fine. Bottom line is this OS is simple enough for a novice and loaded with features for anyone who wants to take advantage of them. Drives a little closer to a Mac but with tons more software applications and flexability. I love runing virtual PC sessions for work and fun and how well it all integrated between Win7 PC's.

product_title: ZoneAlarm Internet Security Suite 2008 - 3 User Pack
review_headline: It had bugs, but they have been fixed
review_body: Well, I have had this software installed on an old Dell Windows 2000 machine and on a new home-built Win XP machine based on an Intel motherboard for less than a year. I can not say that I have been too happy with the overall performance of this product, but it seems to be working well now that it has the latest patches. By the way, they don't tell you that their version 8 and higher software does not work with Windows 2000. So if you want to run an old Win 2K matchine, don't go for this software unless you can get the last of the Version 7 software - version 7.0.483.000. I had the same negative experiences that the above reviewers had, but again, they are now corrected. My XP machine does run the latest version 8 software and it seems to be working great. My Win 2K machine has to run version 7.0.483.000. and it does OK. Can't really complain about the Win2K machine as it is so slow anyway and is no longer supported by Microsoft anyway. Regarding the reviewers that gave this software a 5 star rating. I find it hard to believe that these are legitimate reviews. I would actually suspect these reviews as being sales pitches from the Zone Alarm folks. I find that this company is a little questionable in how they deal with their customers and their customer service. I have seen them delete negative comments on their software from their user forums. They have never lied (that I am aware of), but I simply felt that they do their best to put a rosey picture on their product. As one reviewer above noted, their Tech Support put the blame on my other programs when ZA practically brought my XP machine to its knees. I also was told to disable my other programs until I found \\"the culprit\\". Well I didn't do that. I have those programs on my computer because I want them there. Better that ZA should fix their product, which they eventually did. However, they never simply came out and took the blame for a defective product update. I used to love their freefirewall and this was why I decided to try their full service product. Hopefully these bad experiences were just growing pains that ZA is getting past, but they have damaged their reputation by failing to be completely forthcoming with their customers. The unwritten rule of bad publicity: tell the customer about your mistake, take responsibility for your mistake (with a sincere apology) and then take corrective action.

product_title: MacSpeech Dictate [Old Version]
review_body: I bought this software for transcribing handwritten documents and interviews (I listened to the interviews and repeated the words into the microphone). Unfortunately, it was almost always faster for me to type because the program makes a LOT of mistakes. My interviews and documents have tons of proper names and uncommon older words in them though, so I think MacSpeech might work better for other kinds of dictations or transcriptions. I also find this program to be extremely buggy. It usually crashes at least once per day, even after I installed the updated version. I used MacSpeech quite a bit because my wrists were getting strain injuries from typing, but I usually just ended up getting really frustrated. Maybe with a lot of effort, I could train MacSpeech to better recognize my voice, but I'm not willing to invest more time than it would take me just to type the transcription in the first place. I admire what this program can do, but I don't think I would buy it again.

It was running ok with one annoying problem - it was constantly loosing the video settings every time I reboot. Then these wave of security patch start to roll in. product_title: H&R Block At Home 2013 Premium + State
review_headline: Tax support did not support a form I had to file
review_body:
I have used this program for about 15 years. This year I was very disappointed. I was an enrolled agent some years ago, so I believe I have a better than average knowledge of income taxes. I needed to use a form not used commonly, Form 982, while preparing my son's taxes. When I clicked on help, it said the program does not support this form. It said to open the form, fill in the figures and close the form. I researched on the IRS website.

Next morning, I called H & R Block support. It is only technical support, not tax support. The only way you can get tax support is by live chat. I put live chat in the search bar and it kept telling me their live chat did not support my web browsers. I have a new computer with the latest versions of Google chrome, Internet Explorer and Mozilla Firefox. Back to researching the IRS website. The support technician told me to call the IRS. If I have to do that, why did I buy a tax program that is supposed to have unlimited tax support?

product_title: Intuit Quicken Deluxe 2009
review_body: I have used Intuit's Quicken for many years and have considered Intuit to be one of the best software companies around. However, I was not completely satisfied with my Quicken Deluxe 2009 experience. First of all, since 2007, Quicken has not had a Basic Edition for around $30. I don't need a Deluxe Edition for around $50. That is why I didn't upgrade in 2008, but had no choice in 2009 if I was going to upgrade at all. When I installed Quicken 2009, the program would not run. The Quicken logo flashed on the screen and disappeared. I restarted and reinstalled Quicken. I had the same problem, so I checked what support options I had, as I had never had to contact Intuit support before. I was disappointed, to say the least, that Intuit does not offer free telephone support, but warns of a $25.00 fee. Moreover, Intuit calls you back; you cannot call in directly to get a support agent. So I had to settle for Chat support. I did get the problem resolved, but it took thirty minutes, whereas it would have taken about ten minutes if I had been able to talk to a live person on the phone. It turned out that I did not have the right mapi32.dll. The Chat support agent did pick up this problem pretty quickly, and once the new DLL was installed, Quicken worked. The mapi32.dll problem may not have been Quicken's fault, but I first spent five minutes trying to find troubleshooting help on the Intuit web site, and this solution never came up. I had previously thought that Intuit's help information was the best in the industry. My opinion of Intuit has moderated from 5 stars to 3 stars. Quicken is still probably the best such program around, but 2009 may not be as trouble free as it has been for me over the last ten-plus years.

product_title: SMARTSUITE MIL ED 9.8.2
review_headline: A great suite of programs - I LOVE that I can use Organizer again!!!!!
review_body:
About six months ago, my trusty XP computer that I had used for many years quit working. I knew I didn't want to move to Windows 8 with all the complaints about it not running half the programs I have come to love over the years, so I bought one with Windows 7. I was able to load most of my older and well-liked programs, but was VERY sad that one of my favorite programs of all time wouldn't load - Lotus Organizer. It is, by far, the best program of it's kind ever made!!! I loaded it on my laptop running Vista just so I wouldn't lose all of my contacts or my Christmas Card list, and quit using the daily calendar and to-do functions all together, and started using the crappy alternative in Office. Well, I'm happy to report that I found a version of Organizer that works perfectly in Windows 7 in this suite of programs, and I couldn't be happier!

There are a couple of things I wanted to mention for those who have been trying to do the same thing. First, this entire suite loaded on my Acer running 64 bit Windows 7 flawlessly. Word Pro is almost the same as I remember AmiPro from years ago, and Lotus 1-2-3 is SO much better than Excel. However, if you try to upgrade (convert) your .or2 file from Lotus Organizer release 2 like I did, you'll be disappointed that it won't convert, even if you compact it first. I'm not sure why this version 5 won't convert it because it says it should. But, don't give up like I almost did. The way I worked around this was to export the contacts, anniversaries and any other categories in the older version of Organizer as either ansi or ascii text files and then imported them into the respective categories in this newer version. Every file came through flawlessly doing it that way. After a number of months missing my trusty old Organizer, it's back - and just as good as ever!!!

product_title: Norton Internet Security 2005 - Single User
review_headline: NIS - has the most features - but NO backup!!! - and a UI from Hell
review_body:
(this review is of the Spyware edition)
NIS takes 25Megs of ram - ok for an all-in-one (if you have <256Megs your lightweight CPU can't carry enough armor to make Windows really Zero-day Net safe IMHO)

NIS has most of the features I look for in a firewall/spyware/virus scanner/intrusion detector, BUT
half don't work right, and some that do seem to fight every attempt to make them work.

Even after LiveUpdate this week,
One buggy automatic firewall rule autoloaded, and port 80 was open listening half 'naked' on the Internet.
I replaced it, and at the first passing probe my rule was erased, autoreplaced, naked again.
Only after I stumbled onto the secret trick (add a block all rule after the pass rules) did it close it.
It took 11 clicks (!) just to add the block all rule - miserable!
The log is a nightmare - pages of long sentences explaining \\"permitted once\\" 200 times, no actual info
until I click on one of them. What's worse is, none of them I checked WERE \\"permitted once\\" IIRC.

NIS detected 2 trojan/spywares, but could not remove either.

Enabling program component monitoring started an avalanche of popups, all suggesting I block access, but I actually DO want IE to access the internet.
Running Windows update brought a popup asking if 100's more dll's are ok. How would I know? I do want Windows updated.
Great feature in theory, totally useless even if you know the names of every evil dll not yet invented.

If you have more than 1 or 2 programs not in the automatic ruleset, plan to either \\"permit all\\" or spend many hours actually writing the same set of 3 rules over and over for every autoupdating program you use - assuming you understand TCP vs UDP etc. Why no \\"permit all local + DNS + outbound port 80\\" choice? That would mean 1/10 the work! Jetico lets me pick \\"web browser\\" ruleset, so its UI from Hell gets used once per category.

After spending all day and half the night getting it working, I discover that it is not possible to save my precious rules - or to reload them. I would be less furious if I had a fresh install of windows, but not much.

All good, until a program autoupdates, and 3 more rules to write. Too angry for words.
Jetico lets me clone the old rules or edit them to update the program sig.

I would not use NIS if you paid me 10 times its price.
