product_title: PHP With MYSQL Essential Training
review_headline: Excellent way to learn dynamic web development
review_body: Could you imagine being able to write a site like Amazon.com from scratch? Well if you master everything in this title you will have the basic knowledge toward that end. Even though he creates a real contact management system, the theory is similar and you can continue from there. I taught Math and Computer Science professionally, and I bought this tutorial to learn the specifics of putting together a dynamic website using PHP (I'm a Java, VB, SQL, and C/C++ programmer). I may be a bit biased with my background, but this guy is a top notch instructor and speaker. I sat thru the entire course, even though what I was really interested in was the very practical website he sets up at the end. Many of the concepts in php are built on C and Java. Although its not a language that would win any awards from the Computer Science community (extremely loose typing for example), it is EXTREMELY powerful and will make writing web applications faster and easier. The array and string processing functions are nothing short of remarkable, and make it SO much easier for a new programmer to write effective programs. One line of code turns a delimited string into an array, or vice versa. Sure you can do many of those things in C++, but you would have to be an expert programmer. PHP is wonderful. There is also considerable background on SQL/databases. This title is well worth the money, this course in a private college would be well over a grand. He takes you from installing the necessary software to finalizing a website that can be developed into something much larger. If you have even the slightest background in programming you should be fine. I would give this 4 1/2 stars if I could, because it may require some extra effort for the absolute beginner. If your computer experience consists of web surfing and MS office, depending on your aptitudes you may find it a bit difficult, the same way some people find foreign language or music difficult. Others can start speaking Chinese from a web tutorial. Again it depends on you. I would strongly suggest a pre-requsite of Basic HTML and CSS from free sites such as w3schools (google for others), maybe even a programming tutorial from there. However, the title is very good because many \\"easier\\" tutorials will leave you feeling dry at the end and you won't really have anything to show for it. With my experience in teaching programming languages to newbies, you may have to devote many hours, pause the video and do some googling to solidify these concepts. Becoming a great programmer needs time, patience, and dedication. Do not expect to simply watch the videos and become and expert. Bring a notebook and take notes, type each example into the text editor. Sometimes he will ask you to complete something that he started, and I would be a bit intimidated if I were totally new to programming. I suggest going through those exercises two or even three times until you completely understand it. Again, consider spending a few hours a day for a month to master this material if you are COMPLETELY new to programming. A professional programmer may pick up php fluency in less than a week. This video would be great in a corporate setting to cross train front end web personnel into programming if they are working on a project. Also, considering how web-centric the world is today, even management and non-technical types would benefit from the intimate understanding of what goes into a dynamic-data driven website(he gets into business analysis of the programming situation). Even if you aren't going to do the programming, understanding this title can help you leverage other resources and help you get the best result. Mr. Skoglund also has an advanced PHP video published[...], I will probably be purchasing that too in the near future. http://www.amazon.com/MySQL-Beyond-Basics-Kevin-Skoglund/dp/1596715413/ref=sr_1_3?ie=UTF8&s=books&qid=1253132473&sr=1-3

product_title: Bryce 5
review_body: If your on any kind of budget and start choking when you see $500 or $1,000 for 3D software this is an excellent product. Bryce 5 has an easy to learn interface that allows you to move and alter objects, change atmosphere, and change camera views without having to beat it with a stick. The program lets you save objects, textures, and atmospheres you've created into the program so that they're always there when you come back. It also comes with alot of preset object and textures you can use, so you can create an image the first time you open the program. This isn't the program you want if your trying to do complex character animation, but it's really good for landscapes, architecture, and background. If your not sure this product is for you go to a few 3D sites and look at images people have made with Bryce 5. I've been using it for a year and I'm really happy with it.

product_title: Professor Teaches Office 2013
review_body: Any big-name personal software product, there's probably a "Professor Teaches" for it. These series are well-designed. You can learn in short segments, just a few minutes a day if you like. You can learn basics, or you can go deeper into more advanced features. Nice combination of typical screen demonstrations, having you rehearse manipulating how to do things, and an audio track explaining the thing as you go along. Other helpful features include choosing the location of installation if you like, choosing whether to download all of it or just key parts if space is limited, and picking up where you left off last session. If you want to understand Office 2013, this is a handy product--and the prices for their products have been dropping over the years too.

product_title: Microsoft Windows Small Business Server Standard 2003 (5 Client) [Old Version]
review_body:
I just took on setting up my first small office network. We have four computers and a desktop that someone set up to run as a server. The 6 gig harddrive had long seen its time and needed to be replaced. I bought a Dell PowerEdge SC420, 4 Windows XP Professional upgrades (from Amazon at an amazing price and current rebate) and Windows Small Business Server 2003 (also at a great price). I've worked on PC's for years but never set up a office network with a server. I was very apprehensive and questioned my skill but this software honestly was ridiculously simple to install and deploy.

It guides you through the entire process step by step and I recommend it highly to anyone looking for their first server software. Of course it does have some very technical aspects that left me scratching my head but that's because I don't know what I'm doing. Setting up Sharepoint and Exchange will require some further reading on my part but shouldn't be that difficult to deploy.

I recommend this product very highly and didn't give it 5 stars because of my own inexperience and not being able to see what it can fully do. It also takes hours to install which is pretty typical for any Microsoft product. I did have the whole thing done in one Saturday though and it took about 8 hours altogether.

product_title: The Witcher Limited Edition (Large Box)
review_body:
Were I a member of the gaming Industry right now, I would be shamed to be taught what gaming should look and feel like and how it should be marketed by a small Eastern European company. Who of the multi-billion gaming \\"giants\\" ever went back to improve a released game? Yet, there you have it: thanks to CDPROJECT gaming as an art-form is still alive and kicking!

This was the most awaited fantasy cRPG in the past 3 years. Not only did the original deliver, but even more work has gone into truly improving it.
THIS WAS ONE OF THE MOST BEAUTIFUL cRPG GAMES I HAD EVER PLAYED - AND NOW IT IS GORGEOUS!

The environments are detailed, realistic, and can be experienced from up close. Grass, flowers and tree branches moved in both FABLE and TITAN QUEST as well; these, however, seem so true I caught myself reaching for my...antihistamines! Weather affects and day-night alterations (you have to see the elongating shadows to believe them!) are just gorgeous! More importantly, these are not just eye-candy: certain NPCs and monsters appear only when the correct combination of time-of-day and weather coincide...The horizon is far and the clouds move in endless variations. It reminded me of the sky of the original UNREAL, another visually ground-breaking game at its time. PURE VISUAL MAGIC!

The character (Geralt) can master both sword-fighting and magic spells (what is known as a Warlock). To some die-hard RPG fans this may seem like heresy, nevertheless, keep in mind that multi-classing is not unheard off. The movement repertoire for both practices are impressively designed. Especially the sword-fighting, it is at par to any console action game. And the spells (both offensive and defensive ones) are not less impressive.

Free roaming? Yes and no. One can decide which parts of the map he will visit but loading is still needed to travel even annoyingly short distances. And since quests and side-quest still have to be completed, yes, eventually a subtle, yet ever present, directionality is present.
Looting and bartering? Aaah...yes, sort of. You practically never change the sword you start off with (although you do get to improve its abilities), whereas good armor is only a little easier to come by compared to PLANESCAPE. On the upside, you get to gamble, have romantic relationships (FABLE was full of great ideas after all!) and bribe for information, so trinkets have other uses as well.
Detailed character modifiers? Nothing like the AD&D rules. You gain talents (gold, silver & bronze) which you can spend to improve your fighting or magical abilities. Pretty much like the DIABLO or the TITAN QUEST abilities systems.

So, apart for the slight action-cRPG handicap, I have only two other objections. First, the...camera placement. Once more the atrocious Aurora Engine (remember NWN2...?) will keep auto-placing it where it is bound to get on your nerves - as it targets your character even if that is not the most logical option. Yes, this has indeed improved compared to the original but one cannot teach an old dog new tricks.
Second, the controls. They need getting used to as the fighting combos are still easily ruined by clicking out of sync. You do eventually get the hold of it, however it keeps glitching.

Nevertheless, its shortcomings are not enough to diminish the breath of fresh air this release brings to the scene. The Enhanced edition not only is a truly reworked game but it also comes full with detailed Manuals, beautiful Maps and all the extras that games used to come with in the good old days...

Whereas the BALDUR's GATES saga was story-heavy but (by today standards) visually wanting and the NEVERWINTER NIGHTS series was found, well, wanting in all aspects, THE WITCHER is the dream cRPG that BIOWARE was supposed to be capable of releasing all along but never did - and its current EA bedfellows surely put a stop to such aspirations now. That game, however, is finally here - and not from whom you would expect.
A tip of my hat to CDPROJECT for keeping the ART-FORM of Gaming alive. Well done indeed!

HIGHLY RECOMMENDED!y hat to CDPROJECT for keeping the ART-FORM of Gaming alive. Well done indeed! HIGHLY RECOMMENDED!

product_title: Parallels Desktop 8 for Mac
review_headline: Have the Best of Both Worlds
review_body:
I switched to Mac over 7 years ago. Many business programs, such as Quickbooks and tax software run on a Windows platform. The Mac version of Quickbooks is a shadow of the Windows version. Other programs such as Corel Draw are also Windows based.

Rather than switching between Boot Camp or having a separate PC for these programs, Parallels makes it possible to run the business and graphics software from the same machine and very conveniently. It's only a click of a window to switch between operating systems and programs. The more RAM you have, the better everything works. I can have many programs open simultaneously and switch back and forth easily.

I can print from Windows, through Parallels with the Mac printers. Parallels will recognize the printers, even when their IP addresses change after a restart. Very convenient.

Mac offers a much more stable operating system than Windows. Windows based programs offer more productivity and efficiency. I am really grateful to have the benefit of both worlds.

product_title: Dragon NaturallySpeaking Premium 11 [Old Version]
review_headline: An overrated program with a lot of potential but a lot of rough edges too
review_body:
Pros:

1) capable of decent accuracy with modest training, and very good accuracy with more extended training
2) can keep up with relatively fast speaking meaning overall excellent speed of text generation
3) capacity to train multiple users and work within multiple dialects

Cons:

1) unreliable, crash prone, and buggy - this program needs major work
2) poorly sorted out Windows 7 correction dialog operations (ultra-slow)
3) program becomes unstable when microphone is turned off for protracted periods of time, requiring reinitialization and reloading.
4) program support is a joke - Nuance has to be the most arrogant software company in the world despite some hard working staffers (yup - worse than Microsoft!)

It's almost impossible to be on the Internet or working with the computer and not be aware of Dragon's NaturallySpeaking 11.0. You would think from the relentless advertisement by Nuance that the program never makes a mistake, and allows seamless control of your computer while allowing you to dictate virtually everything. Unfortunately, the hype and promise fall well short of the program's actual functioning.

Although quite good accuracy is possible with modest levels of training, and very good accuracy is possible in technical fields with training of technical vocabulary, the program's buggy operation, recurrent vulnerability to crashing, humongous speech files and subsequent painfully slow loading, and very slow correction interface (much lower for some reason on Windows 7 than on Windows XP) spoil an otherwise enjoyable experience badly.

Although I am almost totally dependent on the program for professional writing (cranking out roughly 20 single spaced pages a day in a scientific area), I am continually amazed with how many rough edges the program has that Nuance seems to be oblivious to, because they recur from edition to edition. As but a small example of lack of attention to relevant details, the program within Microsoft Word does not use the specialized characters for quotation marks, but uses a generic and plainer character set, instead of the one generated within Microsoft Word. This means that if you want professional looking final product, you have to run a macro to replace their generic quotation marks with the proper special character. Although this is a small issue, it's just an example of so many ways in which the program falls down, and displays its lack of polish. It is amazing that despite five editions of the product which I have used that this issue continues, despite feedback from multiple users.

Then there is the issue of loading and speed of operation. With a solid-state drive that gets to the Windows 7 desktop in 20 seconds, it takes 25 seconds to load speech files on NaturallySpeaking 11.0. In other words, an extremely fast hard drive loads a bloated operating system faster than it loads NaturallySpeaking 11.0. I hesitate to think how long it would take somebody to load speech files on the average 250 GB 5400 RPM hard drive. You could go out, mow your lawn, calculate your taxes, then do your email, and come back just in time to start dictating.

Well, so what? Once the program is loaded, things should be okay, right? Well this is where again the program falls down. First of all, actually correcting things reveals a major bug in their Windows 7 code around keyboard input within the corrections dialog box. When you bring up the correction dialog box, you can't type characters without generating a long delay before the program somehow incorporates your keyboard input (roughly 10-12 seconds) - this is unacceptable waiting time for entering a couple of characters. Dictating or spelling out words within the correction dialog box produces somewhat snappier results, but is still amazingly slow, (again running this program on an extremely fast processor, with 6 GB of RAM, and one of the fastest 250 GB solid-state drives). It's scary to imagine how slow this program would be on the average system. In fairness, some of it appears to be a Windows 7 incompatibility, because I use the same speech files and the same 11.0 version on a Windows XP system, and had much snappier response from within the corrections dialog box. Of course Nuance advertises that their code is Windows 7 compatible - something got lost in the translation. But again, this suggests that Nuance is more concerned with their advertising than with the program's actual performance. This is a continuing theme - Nuance's grandiosity gets continually in the way of their ability to see any problems with the program (or their support - which is clearly an industry low-water mark).

The biggest problem though is what happens when you put the program (at least 11.0 - corrected in 11.5) into Suspend by turning off the microphone- and by the way, you are forced to do this because if you simply tell the program to \\"go to sleep\\" any sound into the microphone will cause the page to scroll back to where the cursor is (in other words any kind of sound acts as a reinitialization command to the cursor - the logic behind that completely escapes me! So essentially you are forced to suspend microphone input if you want to scroll through your text instead of the program intrusively interfering with this. This is where things get really interesting (after you turn the microphone off). After about 5 min., the program will malfunction (again only in Windows 7 and not in Windows XP for some strange reason) and give you an error code which the program cannot recover from, and thus all this nonsense requires that you basically start from scratch all over again. This means not simply reloading the program, because the program actually doesn't pull itself out of memory reliably and oftentimes leaves a huge executable sitting in the background (taking up over 300 MB of RAM) - - if you don't kill the program this way, when you try to reinitialize it, you will immediately get the same error code. This means you have to bring up Task manager, find the program, and manually terminate it, and then start from scratch and reload your speech files. This will again take a long period of time - close to 30 seconds with a solid-state drive, A minute and a half with a slow conventional hard drive. All of this nonsense of course significantly deteriorates the productivity advantage associated with dictating versus typing. Indeed, for short pieces of text, all these hassles mean that it is almost always faster to simply type out a couple of paragraphs then it is to struggle with the program. For longer text generation, and assuming that you dictate continuously and don't risk putting the microphone into the off position for any extended period, the program is more productive and faster than typing.

This process of recurrent shutdown and reinitializing (due to fatal program errors) can be very frustrating, and oftentimes has to be repeated multiple times, because if you leave the program on (by not turning off the microphone), and there is any background noise you'll get endless junk words into your dictation space. This brings up another striking failure of the program - its total inability to discriminate speech from background sounds and non-speech noises. The program seems to believe that every conceivable sound must translate into a word, and therefore, any kind of background noise makes it impossible to use the program particularly if you are not using a noise canceling microphone, and instead are dictating on a laptop that has a standard integrated microphone. You would think that the program, which runs on an enormous number of laptops, would be optimized for the standard integrated microphones on laptops. Unfortunately, it is not. You have to use Dragon's headphone microphone gear or some equivalent. Curiously, a much earlier version of the program NaturallySpeaking 8.0seem to work much better with laptop microphone arrays. Why this might be is beyond me.

Because the program code is buggy and unreliable and subsequently the program locks up, you will find that occasionally your speech files are completely trashed and cannot be repaired through Nuance's repair algorithms (there is a speech file Restore function from within the program). This means you had better make a backup copy of your speech files (make that several backup copies), or you will find yourself having to retrain your user identity all over again, from scratch. Additionally, you will find that their optimization program (which gives you the chance to optimize speech files that have had numerous corrections made to them) is not reliable and also locks up regularly. And BTW, its continual crashing will occasionally damage programs with which it is linked, such as Word and Outlook, requiring re-installation of those as well. In other words, this program does not play nice with your system.

In case you're suspicious that these difficulties are unique to my machine, or are a function of viruses, spyware, or other hardware problems, rest assured that none of these issues are remotely responsible for the Programs buggy and unreliable operation. I run two spyware and antivirus programs concurrently, my system is about as fast as a window 7 system can be (Windows experience index 6.7 overall), and I always keep the machine in good working order. Just to clarify, I do tech support for most of my friends on their Windows 7 and Windows XP systems - so the problem isn't that I have a damaged Windows installation that is to blame for these issues.

All of these operational headaches spoil what otherwise might be a useful program. I believe that all of this emerges from Nuance having a very grandiose notion about their software, and not really listening very much to end-users. It's a shame that there is no real competition in the PC marketplace when it comes to dictation software. If there was, I suspect Nuance would have to get their act together because they would quickly lose market share. Given all these issues, 2/5 stars is actually generous. I wish I could make do without the program, or transition to another speech recognition platform, but unfortunately I can't.

Oh, I almost forget the best part: don't expect Nuance to know anything about any of these issues. They have some of the worst technical support I have ever seen in the industry. They blame your system and your computer and claim there are no deficiencies in their program(!).

ADDENDUM:

Dragon 11.5 has just been released and after several weeks - I can see that Nuance has fixed some things, but not touched many others. It no longer crashes as frequently, or generates bizarre error codes as frequently, requiring that it has to be re-initialized regularly - although that still happens. It loads somewhat more quickly. However, it continues to interpret every sound as speech, has a painfully slow corrections dialog, and as per the norm, reaching technical support is like trying to call the Dept. of Defense and you don't have technical support past 90 days. It is painfully obvious that Nuance has no real handle on the program's deficiencies, and therefore it is a 2/5 star program. I can't recommend it.up Task manager, find the program, and manually terminate it, and then start from scratch and reload your speech files. product_title: Powerquest Drive Image 7
review_body:
Works as advertised. I took me 14 mins to create a image of my harddrive to an external firewire drive. The drive had 15 GB of data, and the compressed image was 8.5GB. I wanted to test it to make sure that the product actually works, so I've booted off the included recovery CD, all my controllers were recognized even thou my C: drive is all SCSI and mad up of 3 drives in RAID 0, while the D: drive is a IDE RAID 0 too. The firewire drive was recognized too, so I was able to select the backup image and strat the restore. After 20 min I was able to reboot my newly recovered drive.
The only issue I had is that I use a new motherboard that includes the Intel 1000/100BaseT network chip-set, and the PowerQuest recovery disk did not recognize it, so would've not been able to do a restore by using a network stored image. However this should not be a issue since in the online manual there is information on how to load drivers at boot time, I haven't used the procedure for now.
On more thing, this product is extremlly easy to use. All functions, including the recovery disk use the WindowsXP intreface, not DOS.

product_title: Alsoft DiskWarrior 4.0 for Intel & PowerPC Macs
review_headline: succeeds when Mac's Disk Utility fails
review_body:
I have used each version of this product for close to 10 years now to recover files that would otherwise be lost. Most recently, Mac 10.8 Disk Utility could not repair my system drive after it failed to boot. It even indicated that the disk had to be reformatted (erased). So I booted from an external hard drive loaded with the Mac OS and ran Disk Warrior from there. DW also indicated that it could not replace my directory with the one it had rebuilt. However (this is where the magic happens) the Preview feature was able to mount (make visible) my iMac's internal drive even though Mac Disk Utility couldn't.

From there, I could copy my entire user directory from the iMac over to the external drive, erase the corrupted iMac drive, and start fresh with a new OS. Now I just have to copy my home directory back. I prefer running DW from an external drive because any DVD boot disc such as DW is going to be painfully slow. I recovered 15 GB of data in less than an hour with the external drive. I have dozens of such stories with this software, having used it with Mac friends and colleagues over the years, and thought it was time to give testimony.

product_title: Quicken Deluxe 20
review_headline: Goodbye to Quicken, long time user has jumped ship
review_body:
I am a long time user of Quicken who has decided to jump ship. I am very frustrated with this once-loved program and the level of non-support they currently provide. I AM DONE. Here is my story:

FEB 2, 2015:
Quicken has abolished phone support! I just spent over an hour trying to CHAT my way to resolution on a very basic problem that is inexplicably gob-smacking for them. Here is what happened: My bank changed their log in system and made me select a new username and password. Once I did that, I attempted to update Quicken, but now it won't connect to that bank. Something in the Quicken software doesn't like the change and though I can log in to the bank through a web browser just fine, in Quicken it won't work. Now I have to wait 3-5 days for some advanced department to review my log files and get back to me. Something like this happened last year and back then they fixed in in an hour while I talked to them on the phone. Not having phone support sucks!

FEB 2, 2015: Email from Quicken. This is verbatim and the English is extremely poor.
Hi XXX,
Here is the incident number of our chat session: xxxxxx-xxxxxx. Please expect with in 3-5 business days from our EWC team about your the updates of your issue. Please feel free to contact us again if you still have the same issue after the email has been sent to your email address.
Regards,
Quicken Customer Care

FEB 3, 2015: Email from Quicken
Dear XXX,
We sincerely apologize for any inconvenience that this issue may have caused you. We take great pride at Intuit in providing you with the best possible service and support. It is our goal to make your Quicken experience as enjoyable as possible.
We receive the case that was escalated to our team â€“ Upon checking the Log files associated to your case we found out that your issue will have to be submitted to our scripts team.
To set proper expectations, please be informed that our scripts team will work on your case approximately within 3 â€“ 5 business days.
We will let you know for any progress/resolution of the case once we got feedback from our scripts team.
We appreciate your patience and cooperation towards the resolution of this issue.
Please let me know for any progress/updates on your end.
If you need additional information, please reply to this email with your questions. Be as explicit as possible and I will be happy to assist you further.
Thanks and Regards,
Quicken Customer Care

FEB 10, 2015: Email from me to Quicken
Hello,
It has been 5 business days and I have heard nothing. Are you going to fix this problem? Right now it is a manual process for me, which is painstaking and not worth it.
Thank you,
XXX

FEB 13, 2015: Email from me to Quicken
It has been 8 business days and I have heard nothing. Please respond back with a resolution.

FEB 13, 2015:
I initiated a new chat session to ask for an update. First I was told that work on my issue had halted because I had deactivated my account and that they were waiting for me to reactivate it. This is complete rubbish! Moreover, no one tried to contact me about anything like that - which would have been a requirement. After I said all of this, they quickly recanted and then said they were still working on it and that I would hear back in 2 days.

FEB 17, 2015: Email from Quicken

Thank you for contacting Quicken Customer Care
We sincerely apologize for any inconvenience that this issue may have caused you. We take great pride at Intuit in providing you with the best possible service and support. It is our goal to make your Quicken experience as enjoyable as possible.

I am FINISHED with QUICKEN. All I did was change a user name and password and they still can't figure it out 16 days later??? No thanks!

product_title: Bitdefender AntiVirus Plus 2012 Standard M2 - 3Pc/1 Year [Old Version]
review_body:
I thought an inexpensive A/V with the great ratings BD had received would be a good move. I was terribly disappointed. After installing on 3 machines, all suffered significant slowdowns. The laptops would hang when coming out of suspend, program completely blocked my wireless NIC, took special firewall exceptions and multiple reboots to get it to function. Update is intrusive and timing is poor, browser is noticeably slow with BD running. Product is only suitable for use on a machine that has a constant high bandwidth internet connection. Completely unsuitable for portable machines.

No less than 3 requests for support went unanswered. The 1st couple of \\"we're sorry you're having a negative experience, visit our website and fix it yourself\\" replies were prompt, but once I asked for specific solutions to problems, silence. I asked for a refund... silence. I will have my credit card provider do a chargeback based on the non-response to support requests.

I have removed the program from all my machines, and went back to ESET Nod32, more expensive, but won't screw up my machines, and good protection.

Can't rate it with \\"no stars\\" but would give it negative stars if possible! Simply terrible!!

I figured that I could really use some video editing software that offered more than the software that came with my Canon HD Video Camcorder. I was very happy with the purchase. product_title: Norton Personal Firewall 2002
review_headline: norton personal firewall 2001 was a lot better.
review_body:
If you're just a plain home user who do not want to bother customizing your personal firewall's policy, this is the firewall for you.
On the other hand, if you would rather have a mix of a smart firewall that also gives you the flexibility of fine tuning rules to your needs.... open certain ports (tcp or udp), let certain applications access the internet,... this software can be a bit confusing.
Though the 2002 version lets you do it, it takes a lot more extra steps for one to customize the packet filtering which is a total pain. The 2001 version is a lot more flexible and geared towards the more "savvy" user.
This is one of the few products that pretty much isn't worth an upgrade if you have an earlier version.
On the plus side, functionality is great, it provides good protection and a simple interface.

product_title: Trend Micro Titanium Internet Security 2013 3-Users [Old Version]
review_body:
Decided to give the software a try. Bundled in with a computer purchase. Machine is a middle-shelf 64 bit Windows 8 laptop from a big box outlet. (Purchased specifically for low level college lab work.) Saw all low threat research related web browsing (absolutely no social media, porn, gaming etc). Attributed poor computer performance out of the box to hardware shortcomings.
Upon expiration of the six month Trend Micro license the software was replaced and a complete scan was performed with a new product. Numerous malware found by the new product that had been missed by Trend Micro Titanium.
In fairness, the software was not able to scan the laptop that frequently. It was rarely left on when not in use. It may have performed 6-8 full system scans during the period.
More significant, I noticed that the Trend Micro add in for the two different web browsers I tried to use created instabilities when accessing content on my college websites. The browser would \\"lock up\\" or the homework site would freeze/time out. Flash videos and other media objects were not always accessible. Again, I attributed this to a discount laptop purchase. But this problem has been remedied by the removal of Trend Micro Titanium from this machine. The change was compelling enough to prompt me to write this review.

review_body: Since I have the program my English Pronunciation has improved a lot! It has given me the opportunity to practice at my own pace. product_title: Norton Ghost 14.0 [OLD VERSION]
review_body: The only reason I gave Ghost 14 four stars is because during the backup screens you do not see all the partitions on your hard drive in the default configuration. A novice user would not know that other hidden partitions exist on their computer and would probably not backup them. If the purpose of Ghost 14 is to backup an entire computer then the user should see all partitions that exist on their hard disks as the default configuration. Let the user hide any partition as an option since I know hidden partitions are important too. If your hard disk fails you do want everything back including the hidden partitions. In my opinion the menu configurations of Ghost 14 are more complicated than what it needs to be for the average user. Gone are the days of Ghost 2003 when Symantec would allow a home user to backup all his computers at home with a single copy of Ghost. Now we must all purchase one license of Ghost per PC. The only Reason I purchased Ghost 14 was because DELL messed up their bios on my new laptop so Ghost 2003 would not work with their USB ports. Ghost 2003 would allow you to create your own boot CD disks if you knew how to create boot CD disks with Nero and knew how to modify batch files. You were able to boot Ghost from a CD and backup your entire computer to an external/internal drive or burn a CD or DVD backup. Ghost 2003 is still able to backup all my other computers with Windows Vista and Windows XP (32bit and 64bit versions). The Ghost 14 bootable CD only restores images and does not have any backup software available so it behaves like a rescue CD. All backups in Ghosts 14 are conveniently done when logged in to a Windows XP or Windows Vista account unlike Ghost 2003 which requires you to use a bootable CD, USB Drive, or floppy disks.

product_title: Parallels Desktop 4.0 for Mac [OLD VERSION]
review_headline: Paralles 4.0 over Fusion, Virtual Box, and Crossover
review_body: First off, I am here to testify that Parallels 4.0 is the best solution to running Windows apps on Mac OS X. I have tried Crossover (Crossover Games too), VMWare Fusion 2.0, and Sun's Virtual Box. Crossover([...]) is a good solution if you just want to run one windows app but anymore and it becomes a really big headache (if are not a computer engineer/programer). Virtual Box ([...]) is great if you like free stuff but again same thing with Crossover, if you are not a computer engineer/programmer it's a very difficult application. VMWare Fusion 2.0 (http://www.amazon.com/Smith-Micro-Software-Inc-VMFM20BX2/dp/B001F5VBRU/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&s=software&qid=1252022776&sr=8-1)is great to run Windows apps but can be slow at times. I first bought Fusion about a month ago. I have been reviewing all of these products since I bought my Macbook Air, yes I said Air, in January 2009: these are my results. I tried VMWare first because at that time it had the best reviews. These are the operating systems I have used on VMWare Fusion 2.0 and Virtual Box: Linux Ubuntu 9.04, Windows XP Professional, Windows 7 Ultimate (32-bit RC), and Sun Open Solaris 10. VMWare doesn't work with Open Solaris very well (I haven't tried Open Solaris with Paralles yet), in Virtual Box Open Solaris worked pretty good. I say this up front Windows XP works great with all three virtual machines, not a problem. Windows 7 does not work in Virtual Box, period but works in VMWare Fusion 2.0 very slow. Windows 7 runs great under Paralles. Crossover doesn't even support anything past Windows XP. Ubuntu 9.04 worked pretty well with VMWare Fusion and Virtual Box (again, haven't tried Paralles yet). The biggest issue I found with Virtual Box is the fact that wireless internet is not useable in the guest machine nor does shared folders work at all (on any of the OS's). The biggest issue with VMWare Fusion is friendliness, Paralles just looks much better and again just works without issues. Overall, I rate this product to be the best of the best virtual machines out there to date. NOTE: IF YOU WANT A PRODUCT THAT JUST WORKS GO WITH PARALLES 4.0. product_title: Better Homes and Gardens Home Designer Suite 7.0 [OLD VERSION]
review_headline: Know What the Program is NOT Before You Buy
review_body:
I think this can be a fun suite of programs if you like to speculate about how a new project in your house or yard might turn out. A reasonable library of materials and a relatively simple design process allow you to create rough approximations.

There are software limitations, however, that will frustrate perfectionists. Design angles are limited to 7.5 degree increments, for instance, so getting the exact angle of your hedge, angled sidewalk, or slanted driveway may not be possible if that angle isn't divisible by 7.5 degrees.

Another example of limitations is that the roofing application makes no provision for certain circumstances in which two sections of roof have different slopes. The result is that you can't really recreate the roof on an L-shaped house unless the two branches of the L are the same width. I thought this was a user error until I found that the tech support solution was to widen the thinner section of the house to get the roof to line up right.

In short, the program is not going to provide architectural specs for a house or a reliable blueprint for landscaping your yard. Perfectionists will have to just \\"let it go\\" after a certain point. That having been said, the software IS fun if you are the sort of person who enjoys design software.

product_title: Quicken 2008 Premier [OLD VERSION]
review_body:
(This is a drastically revised review. My initial installation experience was good, and I rated the program 5 stars. Now I rate it at 1-star.) Here's the recap.

I dreaded the upgrade from Quicken 2005 to 2008. I waited as long as possible, then validated my data, etc., and set aside a day when I thought I could stand the frustration. Whaddaya know, the installation went pretty easily, and soon I was up and running, intact, or so I thought. I use Quicken BillPay and have for years, and I have Windows XP Pro. My online billing proceeded normally, and I was greatly relieved. I even submitted a 5-star review. The program does little more than Quicken 2005 did, but the new eye-candy was pleasant, and the upgrade was mandatory. By waiting as long as possible to install, the program was already on Version 7 (God help early adopters!)

Then I noticed that my checking account appeared as \\"Wachovia Securities\\" when the correct account was and always has been \\"Wells Fargo\\". I tried all the obvious ways to fix it, and nothing worked, so I thought I'd give the new \\"chat\\" support a try. When it became clear that the things the support person suggested wouldn't work, she simply disconnected!! That solved HER problem. And I decided not to sweat it, since the erroneous name didn't seem to cause any other problems.

But then -- I pulled up an old saved report from Q2005, and one column of data was garbage. This time I tried email support. Through an exchange of emails, they advised me to validate the file, and if that didn't work, to supervalidate it. I did all of that (very carefully, I had a backup, but by the way the normal backup you get is worthless, more on that), and it still didn't work. The email guy said I should phone in and talk to a support person.

AND THEN I noticed that the validation process had ELIMINATED ALL RECORD OF ONLINE TRANSACTIONS AND ALL OF MY ONLINE PAYEE LIST, which was substantial!! Oh woe. This is when I tried restoring a backup file I'd made the day before. But get this: WHEN QUICKEN 2008 MESSES UP, IT DOES SO IN A WAY THAT PREVENTS YOU FROM GOING BACK TO A PREVIOUSLY FUNCTIONAL VERSION. Every old file I \\"restored\\" now showed the same total absence of online transactions and onlinei payees. Now I did decide to phone in for support.

I was pleasantly surprised: Without a long wait time, I was connected to a young woman in Bangladesh or some other remote location, but she was really really sharp and actually solved the problem. This was not trivial. I had to cancel my online billing setup, validate and revalidate and revalidate the file until no \\"corrected errors\\" showed up, and then reinstate online billing. We basically took Quicken apart and put it back together again. She also corrected the account so that Wells Fargo showed up instead of Wachovia, although this was separate from the issue that had wiped out my online transactions. As far as the column of garbage in the saved Q2005 report, she said that Q2008 does that sometimes; I should just delete the report and recreate it. All these problems were solved, my online payee list was restored, and at that point, I was charged $24.95 for the call. I tried to argue that Q2008 had created the problem and corrupted my file, but decided to blow it off and just pay and be done with it. I thought my problems were over. Ha.

BECAUSE THEN, when I next \\"updated\\" my online accounts, Quicken Bill Pay downloaded the LAST TWO YEARS OF TRANSACTIONS, roughly 650, along with a few new ones interspersed. The balance in my checking accounted was now -$87,000. That's MINUS $87,000.

In the next call to phone support I found out that \\"That's just how it is\\". I would have to go through the last 2 years of transactions and manually delete the duplicates. (He did tell me to sort the account by \\"most recently entered\\" instead of by \\"date\\", so I was able to select groups and delete with only 1-2 clicks per transaction instead of the 4-5 clicks it normally takes to delete a transaction.) At the end of all this, my accounts have been somehow \\"unreconciled\\" -- all records of the last month's reconciliation have been eliminated. So I'm having to redo that too. I don't actually expect my bank account to balance at the end of all this (How do you carefully and thoughtfully delete duplicate records when you're feeling like !@#%$?) I plan to just enter a fudge factor and forget about it.

Here's some learnings: If you're converting from an old version, and you decide to validate the file before you start the conversion, keep rerunning the validation routine until it turns up no more error messages. They don't tell you this, but the sharp woman said that was important. Then you may or may not want to \\"super-validate\\" which you do by holding down the shift key while you go thru the validation procedure.

Then you can pray a lot. If your bank account name comes up wrong, try ignoring it. If your old reports look funny, delete and recreate them. Do anything you can to avoid using the Q2008 version of validation.

If you need support, go immediately for the phone support. I talked to 2 people, and both knew what they were doing. The first woman was awesome (except for not telling me the horrors that would happen the next time I ran the online update). The second person, a guy, knew I was, well, screwed, and he tried to be as nice as possible about it. I have used Quicken since 1998, and I will say that support is better than it was a few years ago (not close to the way it was Back in the Day), and they don't charge you unless they solve the problem. The chat and email support were useless.

All for now.a transaction.) At the end of all this, my accounts have been somehow \\"unreconciled\\" -- all records of the last month's reconciliation have been eliminated. So I'm having to redo that too. I don't actually expect my bank account to balance at the end of all this (How do you carefully and thoughtfully delete duplicate records when you're feeling like !@#%$?) I plan to just enter a fudge factor and forget about it. Here's some learnings: If you're converting from an old version, and you decide to validate the file before you start the conversion, keep rerunning the validation routine until it turns up no more error messages. They don't tell you this, but the sharp woman said that was important. Then you may or may not want to \\"super-validate\\" which you do by holding down the shift key while you go thru the validation procedure. Then you can pray a lot. If your bank account name comes up wrong, try ignoring it. If your old reports look funny, delete and recreate them. Do anything you can to avoid using the Q2008 version of validation. If you need support, go immediately for the phone support. I talked to 2 people, and both knew what they were doing. The first woman was awesome (except for not telling me the horrors that would happen the next time I ran the online update). The second person, a guy, knew I was, well, screwed, and he tried to be as nice as possible about it. I have used Quicken since 1998, and I will say that support is better than it was a few years ago (not close to the way it was Back in the Day), and they don't charge you unless they solve the problem. The chat and email support were useless. All for now.

product_title: VMware Fusion 2 [OLD VERSION]
review_headline: Not perfect yet, but getting there
review_body:
I've been a Parallels user for some time and at the moment still use Parallels for a Windows XP installation.

When VMWare Fusion first came out I had downloaded it, not because I was unhappy with Parallels, but because I needed to run an OS that Parallels couldn't install but that I knew worked under VMWare on other platforms.

That OS is SCO Unix - I still have a handful of SCO customers left (just a handful, fortunately) so from time to time I need to access a SCO box to remind myself how something works or to test something before I inflict it upon my customer.

As I hoped, VMWare installed and ran SCO perfectly. Well, almost - I still haven't got the mouse to work in the GUI but for my purposes I really don't need that - I can always vnc in if need be. I did have a little trouble getting the network to work - I wanted it to dhcp but it wouldn't, so I finally just gave it a hard address and all was fine.

As it happened, the next day I needed to test something on the latest Centos so I installed that under VMWare rather than Parallels and of course that was 100% perfect - no issues whatsoever.

I see that VMWare now has the ability to convert a Parallels install.. I haven't done that yet, but really, why should I run both of these?

And Parallels does seem to be a very busy boopy - I happened to be running \\"opensnoop\\" and noticed that Parallels has a LOT of activity.. I noticed nothing from Fusion during that same period. Now Parallels was running Windows and Fusion was doing Centos, so it might be Windows fault, but I would guess VMWare is going to be more efficient if it isn't already. I think they've just had more experience and resources.

I've read many reviews that show Fusion as faster - and I do notice that my XP is slow.. of course XP is often sluggish anyway, but I think I'll be doing that conversion soon.

product_title: Webroot SecureAnywhere Internet Security Plus 2013 - 3 Devices
review_body: I bought this from Amazon for about $19 incl shipping. It got to me by regular mail 4 days after I placed my order. $19/3 computers = $6.33 per machine for internet security. I previously tested all the major competitor's products in real time for 30 days each. Some passed a lot of malware, some bogged the computer down, some interfered with my e-mail and some allowed viruses to pass. I have run real-time tests with malware scanners and sandboxes on my machines. Of the several products I tested, this one has come closer to a perfect score than the others. My malware scanners come up with zero malware now most of the time and the competing products always passed some each day. This product is the least invasive of any other - meaning it doesn't bother me with pop-ups at all and doesn't slow my computers down. I worry less about malare and viruses now and enjoy my computer time most using this product. It auto-scans each day unnoticed. If I use the scan button, it takes less than 2 min to do a full scan. Add the fact that I got it so cheaply and fast, then I have something to be very happy about. How would I rank the competition? #2 Norton. (it's almost as good), like all the competition the scans take quite awhile. #3 Kaspersky - doesn't bog the machine badly but passes malware. #4 BitDefender - heavy program, does the A-V job effectively, passess malware, uses noticeable computer power. #5 ESET - not a resource-heavy program but I didn't test it as heavily as the rest but it gave me no real problems that I recall. AVG- best of all the free ones. Panda- it passed a Trojan to my machine. IOLO AV, crashes and needs re-install fairly often - I had it for a year. Very weak AV. Trend Micro - About as good as IOLO, maybe slightly better.

product_title: Microsoft Windows 8 Pro - Upgrade [Old Version]
review_body:
I bought this product in October 2012 and it never seemed to work correctly. Later, I found that it needed \\"activation\\". When I very carefully entered the 25 character product key, the program rejected it and refused to activate the program. By the time I got around to this the product was not returnable at Amazon.com and I was forced, by Amazon, to contact Microsoft for a fix.

The Microsoft phone number initially offered by Amazon was incorrect. The second number offered by Amazon got through to a dispatcher who issued a service ID and was transferring me to a technical representative. That line was disconnected during the wait. I called Microsoft again with the ID and was told there would be a 19-35 minute wait. I insisted. Eventually, a representative verified that my original product key was valid, even though it wouldn't activate my software. She issued a new product key that worked and which eliminated the assorted problems experienced with the software.

If you buy this Microsoft software:

1. Failure to activate the software causes strange and unattributed problems.

2. ===> BEWARE THAT THE PROVIDED ACTIVATION KEY MAY NOT WORK! <====

3. If you don't act quickly, Amazon won't be of much help.

4. Getting service from Microsoft is a painful and time-consuming task.

The cost of time wasted would have paid the differential cost in moving to a Macintosh system. There's no future for a company who can't even do activation properly!

product_title: Parallels Desktop 3.0 for Mac - Old Version
review_headline: Near Perfect With Boop Camp Partition
review_body: I bought Parallels for Mac because of previous problems with other similar program, VM Ware. In all fairness, the VM product was a beta so I should have guessed it would be buggy, but even the non beta version had its fair share of bugs. Although VM Ware loaded XP home without a hitch, using the program was fraught with difficulties. First, it was slow as molasses in January. Im not taking just a little slow, Im talking go to lunch and maybe itll be finished slow. Secondly, it was prone to mouse failure. Although it would recognize my mouse, it was always at least 2 inches off the mark. If I wanted to click a box I finally learned to position my mouse at least 2 inches below the intended button and then click. Finally, VM Ware allows for the import of an existing Boot Camp partition (see below) but the process is slow and one slight misstep spells doom. For the novice, its intimidating. Then I went to Boot Camp, which is Apples built in Windows capable utility. It worked without a hitch but you had to reboot to either OS X or Windows and hold the option key to get a boot menu. Of note, Boot Camp runs Windows natively, that is, at the same speed as a regular Windows machine. Fact is, it runs quicker on a Mac! All you have to do is go to the Boot Camp utility (under Utilities in the HD icon) and it walks you through it. I got Parallels because I was tired of rebooting my computer to get to Windows. I use Quicken 2008 quite a bit and Quicken for Mac really bites so I do have to use Windows. With Parallels I dont have to reboot. How difficult is it to access the Boot Camp partition with Parallels? Well for starters, it takes about as long as reading this sentence. Once you install Windows into Boot Camp you then install Parallels in Mac. Upon opening Parallels the first time itll ask you if you want to import the Boot Camp partition with Windows on it. Click yes and youll get a desktop icon that states My Boot Camp. After afew minutes of tweaking youll have Windows running on your Mac desktop. Of course, its not all fun and games. For example, youll get a warning that your Windows serial number is no longer any good because of significant hardware changes on your computer. Not a problem. I called the Microsoft toll free number and they issued me a new serial number when I told them what happened. Also, until Parallels recognizes and installs your mouse in the window, youll have to revert to the old ALT routine (the underlined Y in Yes means you have to press the Y key to enter the command. Making things weird is that you sometimes have to hit the ALT or CTRL key, sometimes you dont. Go figure). Also, you must learn to read instructions. Your mouse cursor will be stuck in the Parallels window that appears. It will seem you cant get it out of the box. Read the bottom of the box and itll tell you to hit CTRL and ALT to get the cursor out of the box and back to Mac. It you go to full screen mode, youll have to remember to key in ALT and ENTER to access the Mac screen again (it merely minimizes the window that has XP or Vista in it). By the way, the default memory allocated to Parallels is 512 MB. Some may find this a tick slow and you can increase it to half of your available RAM if you desire (I have 4 GB so I could go to 2). I found 512 to be just about right, but Vista will require at least 1 GB. If done properly, Windows will act just as fast in Parallels on Mac as it does in Boot Camp. I could detect no discernible difference, but there are a couple things to remember: 1. If Windows is open in Parallels, shut it down as you would any Windows machine. Shutting it down by closing the window may make it crash. 2. Maximize the window for best performance. If you use the default window size things get really crowded very quickly. 3. Dont think you can get away using a hacked or cloned version of Windows. Parallels demands a serial number before it will load Windows, unless you import it from Boot Camp and then Windows asks for a serial number. Either way, youre out of luck if you attempt to use a fraudulent copy. For the price I paid (about $20 when I bought my Mac) you really cant lose with Parallels. It works as intended and actually runs Windows better than a Windows machine.

review_headline: The Magix Pro That I Know
review_body: After using the Magix Pro series for the past 3 years, I had an opportunity to run some competing video editors, including Sony Vegas and Cyberdirector, to see if there would be any rendering advantages in other software formats. I discovered that the nomenclature of most video software these days is so different between programs, that it requires a complete retraining of processes in order to get results, which I found myself unwilling to do. The 'comfort' of the Magix interface, coupled with a good book-sized publication included in the package, made it a compelling choice for me to decide upon acquiring MX Pro 18. While its rendering times are not the fastest in the industry, the amount of video and audio tools included in the package (audio recordists take note, this is as good as Pro Tools for a computer multitrack solution!) make the program one of the most powerful in its price range.

For example, it runs \\"background scans\\", meaning when the scan is running, it's in the \\"background\\" and is not supposed to affect the performance of your computer while you're working. product_title: TurboTax Deluxe Federal + E-File + State 2012
review_headline: mostly the same, but in some ways it's worse
review_body:
I've used TurboTax to do my taxes for many years, in some years I used TaxCut (or whatever it's called now). I've generally found TT to be slightly better, but not dramatically so, and therefore have in the past recommended that buyers consider price as an important factor in the decision.

This year I'm in the position of being able to compare the Deluxe & Premier versions, and so far can comment in detail on the investment-related features, which is where they differ.

But first: if you're not familiar with TurboTax -- it really is a good option for preparing your taxes if you are a do-it-yourself person, comfortable with going to the IRS website or other tax info sources to get answers to questions. No, TT will NOT, despite the grand marketing claims, take care of you if you're not quite sure about the rules or are confused about some little tax detail that's not either simple or common.

If you aren't very comfortable with figuring out the rules, then you might want to have a tax advisor available who can answer questions and perhaps also review your return before you submit it.

Now to this year's program: it mostly looks the same as last year's, and the basic workflow seemed familiar and easy to follow. I do like the fact that you can either follow the easy guided path (EasyGuide) or navigate on your own. The dowload options for W2s and 1099s are comprehensive (you can find lists on the Intuit website), but note that Paychex is apparently (still) not supported.

1. If you have tax-exempt dividends from a multi-state muni fund, TT doesn't allow to enter the fraction or amount of the dividend that's from your state (so tax-exempt in your state return). They want you to split the 1099 into two parts, one for your state and one for the others. This is just DUMB. A product that generates $1.5 billion in revenue deserves a bit more care & attention.

2. This year you'll start seeing the complexity that the IRS created with the basis reporting on sales of stocks and mutual funds. The problem is that some sales are \\"covered\\", meaning that the basis has to be reported to the IRS (using your chosen basis method), and others are reported as sales, but basis is your job. I found that sorting through this stuff is mind-bending and error-prone, to a large extent because of the shockingly poor job TurboTax does at helping you work through this. A simple table-type structure where you could quickly enter, review, and correct all the transaction data isn't hard to imagine. But imagine is all you can do because of the horrible interface you'll get in TT. I even went into the Forms interfaces, looking at the imported 1099B and the 8949 and the Cap Gains Worksheet -- unfortunately it's even harder to work with those.

3. If you have investment transactions, you should probably cough up the extra money and get the Premier version. With the Deluxe version the security names & transaction descriptions are not downloaded correctly: For example, \\"1000 shares of XYZ\\" shows up as \\"EXCH to ABC\\" in my case with a 1099B. (Being cynical, I'm thinking that this is an intentional feature degrade, to \\"persuade\\" us to buy Premier.) With a 1099Div, the payer name was simply \\"Vanguard\\", instead of the name of the fund, which is not ideal because you want the name on the return to match the name on the report going to the IRS.

That's all I have for now, I'll try to write an update when I'm done with my taxes. Hope this helps!

Note (Jan 27):
I found another area where TT doesn't handle things well, but it's likely to be quite rare: I have a foreign bank account, which earned interest. I couldn't find an obvious place to enter (foreign) interest not reported on a 1099, so entered it in the 1099 workflow, filling in the required details. I had already generated a Form 1116 because of mutual fund foreign income. However, TT did not add the new data to the existing 1116, or generate a new one.. It only flagged this during the error check, and essentially said \\"you made a mistake, go do the form\\". Not what I expected.

Note (Feb 16):
Another funny thing: I downloaded Vanguard brokerage 1099, and it seems that only the first sale (capgain) transaction was imported. I can't tell easily whether this is a Vanguard glitch or a TT glitch. Either way, watch out for stuff like this seems to be the appropriate conclusion.w data to the existing 1116, or generate a new one.. It only flagged this during the error check, and essentially said \\"you made a mistake, go do the form\\". Not what I expected.

Note (Feb 16):
Another funny thing: I downloaded Vanguard brokerage 1099, and it seems that only the first sale (capgain) transaction was imported. I can't tell easily whether this is a Vanguard glitch or a TT glitch. Either way, watch out for stuff like this seems to be the appropriate conclusion.

product_title: Pinnacle Studio 9 [OLD VERSION]
review_body: I like my Pinnacle but it can be frustrating at times. I just had to learn some patience and take it slow. Let it do it's thing before you move on clicking away. I got lucky when my computer had a meltdown and I lost everything. I had a DVD of some of my work to see how it looked on the TV. It was only 11 minutes long and had several video clips with music and some transitions. I imported it from my file menu and used it as I continued working on my project. I re-rendered this project and it rendered very fast since all the parts of the this segment had already been pre-rendered. This gave me the idea to make my full movies with several DVD's like \\"Acts\\" in a play. I make a few minutes of my show with all the bells and whistles i want and then render that segment on a DVD R/W and do this until my show is finished. My Dad's Vietnam documentary was broke up into 6 different DVD's. I then import all of them and drag and drop them into my timeline and render the entire movie on one single DVD. If any small glitches exist i fix them but keep that to a dull roar! the whole idea is to keep the overall work load down to a minimum - like re-tracking some music or adding a transition etc... and then I render the entire project. My first disk on the documentary is 59 minutes long with lots of music, tons of video i took on my panasonic mini DV with a lot of transitions and effects. Since all of the segments of my disk were all PRE-RENDERED the whole project rendered very fast and did not CRASH!!! and this has worked on other projects for me as well. I have a Sony Vaio computer with Windows XP Home Edition Ver. 2002 with a Pentium 4 CPU 3.06 GHz - 1 Gig of RAM and 200 GB of Drive D space.I hope this helps others on their projects and good luck movie making.

NX2 is a very solid piece of software, it does what a photographer needs to do, if you are into design than you need Photoshop. I really feel like Nikon designed this for the everyday photographer to the serious hobbyist. The interface is a bit different if you have used other programs in the past, but many of the shortcuts are close to other ones, that it should not take you long to get up and running. In comparing this with Lightroom, both offer very similar features,and it really depends on your flavor. Like other reviewers have stated, you can get a free trial from Nikon for 60 days, so get it and play around with it.

product_title: INDIVIDUAL Home Design Quick & Easy 2.0 (Windows)
review_headline: Easy to use, but not perfect
review_body:
I went ahead and bought this program based on the reviews and its price. I must say that if you have used any other CAD program or the Visio building stencils, this will be an easy program to learn. I opened the my first drawing and started putting together my new house right away.
Creating the rooms were very simple. There were a few times I had to search for an answer (like how to use a jogged wall to create an entry way), but for the most part it was pretty simple.
The main gripe I have with this program is the lack of objects. One area that is totally missing is electrical. You can place where lights belong in the house, but there is no objects for electrical outlets, light switches, phone jacks, or cable/Internet connections. I was surprised because I consider these to be major features.
The other issue I have with the program is that when you print your layout there is alot of whitespace surrounding your drawing. If you try to increase the image size then your drawing gets placed on multiple pages.
Other than these issues I think the program is great. If you are looking for an easy to learn program that will give you the ability to layout your furniture, this program is for you.

product_title: Sanus Systems LL11-B1 51 x 80-Inch Ultra-Thin Flat Panel Mount for TV
review_headline: Low profile mount - but too low profile?
review_body:
I purchased this mount because I wanted to mount my Samsung 63\\" [[ASIN:B003A7X5HU Samsung PN63C8000 63-Inch 1080p 3D Plasma HDTV, Black]] as close to the wall as possible, and this seemed to be the lowest mount available with the exception of the Samsung picture frame style mount, but that mount was over $200 and I had qualms about the stability of that mount (just mounts into the drywall - no thanks).

I had read some of the negative reviews about this ultra low profile mount where users had a problem with having room for wires. On my Samsung, the inputs are oriented towards the side of the TV, so I figured I'd have plenty of room for wires.

Installation wasn't too difficult, but the included instructions were pretty bad. I didn't find out until after installing that they have a video instruction on the Sanus website - I highly recommend viewing before installation. One thing to make sure you do before mounting the TV, is make sure you adjust the strings behind the TV so they hang down low enough (almost as low as the bottom of the TV) that you can reach them. You will need to pull these strings to make adjustments, plug in your inputs, or remove the mount later - so neglecting to adjust the strings prior to mounting, as I did on my first pass, can leave a major headache (I was able to fish them from behind the TV, and I removed the TV from the mount and adjusted the wires correctly and remounted ... again, had I watched the video I wouldn't have made this mistake in the first place).

So why 3 stars? Well I have a couple of problems with this mount. The bracket that attaches to the TV grips the top of the wall mount, then is supposed to \\"click\\" into place at the bottom in order to form a secure mount. Problem is, if there is anything back there at all blocking the TV, it won't click into place. This is the problem some of the negative reviewers who have TVs with inputs facing backwards have - it didn't leave any room for the HDMI or other input cables. In my case, my cables are perpendicular to the TV and don't seem to be the problem. What's even worse than the lack of clicking, is my TV isn't quite flat against the wall - the front of the TV is a little under 2\\" from the wall on the left side, and a little over 2\\" from the wall on the right side, for a difference of over half an inch. I think my culprit might be, the wall I have it mounted on is in a spot where an exterior concrete block wall meets an interior wall, with a sheet of drywall over the interior and the drywall has a very very slight (barely noticeable, and in fact not noticeable at all had I never tried to mount this to it) bulge to it. I think that very slight roundness is what is causing my problems with this mount. Yes, I realize this is mostly my own problem as I don't have a perfectly smooth mounting surface - but my point is, this \\"ultra slim\\" mount by leaving only .55\\" inches behind the TV leaves you almost no room for error. If there is any obstruction, including wires or anything else, you could have problems.

Other than that, the quality of this product is pretty good. The one week spot I would point out, and I haven't tested it for failure, but the mechanism where you pull the strings to release the lock seems pretty flimsy. If this mechanism were to fail, you would potentially find it extremely difficult to remove the TV from the wall. And again, with the extremely low profile of the mount at only .55\\", you'd have very few options to get back there and try to get the thing loose.

Overall, this isn't a terrible product, but I have to recommend it with reservations. If, like most TVs, the inputs on your TV face backwards requiring some room for wires, I would look for a mount that isn't quite so close to the wall. Similarly, if your wall is anything but perfectly flat and smooth (get up with your eye next to your wall and look, the imperfection I'm talking about is not noticeableotherwise), this mount could give you problems. On top of that, the flimsy string mechanism would worry me a little bit as well. Finally, if your setup can accommodate an ultra low profile mount and you do decide to buy this product, make sure to watch the installation video on the Sanus website, and if installing into concrete, I'd go out and buy better anchors than what comes with this mount.

3 Stars. Under perfect conditions it probably works fine and it does get the TV nice and close to the wall, but frankly I wish I'd just bought a less low profile mount to start with - it would end up looking just as good with much less hassle. I will probably replace this mount with one that has a little more forgiveness, likely one of the cheaper Amazon Basics models that get good reviews.oblems. On top of that, the flimsy string mechanism would worry me a little bit as well. Finally, if your setup can accommodate an ultra low profile mount and you do decide to buy this product, make sure to watch the installation video on the Sanus website, and if installing into concrete, I'd go out and buy better anchors than what comes with this mount. 3 Stars. I will probably replace this mount with one that has a little more forgiveness, likely one of the cheaper Amazon Basics models that get good reviews.

product_title: Flips Audio Collapsible HD Headphones and Stereo Speakers
review_body:
I received these headphone straight from Flips audio themselves, I took there try before you buy challenge. I used them over a couple of weeks to them an honest try. I used them as headphones and also used the unique feature and as the name suggests the ear cups flip out 180 degrees to act as powered amplified portable speakers.

Here is the break down of the head phones.

Presentation.
The overall presentation of the headphones are very nice from the sleek packaging stating all the aspects of the headphones to the ample amounts of padding used to secure the headphones themselves. The headphones themselves are stored inside a semi hard shell. The. Hard shell itself Is more of an egg shape to accommodate the headphones in their folded positions. Inside the case comes the headphones in their folded position and a USB charging cable to charge the battery that is used when the headphones are used in the flipped out speaker position.

Build quality
The overall build quality of the headphones are a mixed bag. Some parts are built for use and abuse, like the sturdy metal hinges that are used when folding the phones to store them. While other parts seem just a little too weak for the job at hand. Ie. the pivot points of the actual ear cups have a very slight wobble when you flip out the ear cups to use as head phones. I do not know if they are designed that way or not. Also the headphones are a tight fit, after using them for an extended time the pressure of the head phone can be felt on the temples, even more so if you use glasses.

Sound quality

The sound of the headphones are good but not great. The sound range of the headphones seem to be somewhat limited are a bit flat. Mind you all of the sounds are their and can be heard. But the overall mix of the speakers seems to limit what these speakers are actually capable of doing.On the up side they do sound much better when they are flipped out and usedas powered speakers.

Overall

These headphones are descent headphones. But there are a few nuances That seems to keep these headphones from being great. I.e. the tight fit and the limited soundscape of the earphones keep these head phones from being a great pair.

I hope this honest review of these head phones help the maker consider some minor changes to these to make these head phones a great pair.

But as with all reviews it is up to you to come up with your own conclusion.

product_title: Sony NTM-910 900 MHz BabyCall Nursery Monitor, NTM910
review_body: We had used a Sound and Lights monitor for our first child, but when the baby came along and we needed a second monitor, I chose this one because of the many channels. I wanted to make sure that there wouldn't be interference with our first monitor. The difference between the two monitors is overwhelming! This monitor does not make popping/crackling noises, or that odd bounding noise that my sounds and lights monitor does. In addition, the monitor really picks up the baby sounds well and makes them stand out over the background noise. We play a white noise machine (washing machine noise) and the noise cancelling feature does not eliminate this as background noise- however, it does minimize the sound in comparison to the babies noise in both modes. I cannot begin to say how wonderful the lack of static etc is, not to mention the choice of 27 channels! My only complaint is that using this monitor has made me supremely dissatisfied with my older monitor- so I may have to buy a second Sony!

product_title: Sennheiser Closed Circumaural Hi-Fi Headphone
review_headline: Comparable sound, not comparable comfort to the HD555s
review_body:
I just purchased these to replace my HD555s at work. Aaaand - I just printed the return label.

I love my 555s, but the open design is not ideal for a shared workspace. There's substantial two-way leakage, meaning that, in order to block out my more obnoxious cube mates, I must jack up the volume... in turn contributing to the general obnoxiousness!

On the other hand, the 555s are the most comfortable pair of cans I've ever put on, and I can wear them for an entire day with minimal fatigue. I've got some seriously sensitive ears, and even a bit of pressure or displacement becomes very uncomfortable quite quickly.

Upon opening, I was immediately concerned with the slightly less space in the cups, and the leather-like padding material (in contrast to the 555's velour-y padding). FWIW, I was aware of the leatherette cups at purchase, and thought I could probably live with it, (hoping they'd not be too sweat-inducing). I had, however, purchased the 448s hoping that sticking with the brand would mean the same voluminous cups. Alas, it proved not to be so.

Along with the above concerns, I wasn't impressed with the build quality by comparison. The whole kit was very plastic seeming and the cord was noticeably more flimsy than my triple-5 friends.

I gave the 448s an hour. I immediately noticed the outside attenuation, which was a good start, but also noticed a bit more pressure and less room in the cans. Sound was good through the laptop -> E5. Maybe a bit less transparent, but that was expected, and asked for. I didn't experience major discomfort, but I was *aware* of them the entire time, and thinking about how long it would be until I was going to experience cumulative discomfort.

Then the decisive moment - I put the 555s on to compare. Ahhhhhh. Little fluffy clouds.

Take note, Herr/Fraulein Sennheiser - closed version of the 555/558/595 design will be in my shopping cart the moment I am aware of such a product.

So, back go the 448s, sadly, and obnoxious co-workers will continue to be battled with reciprocal obnoxious volume-raising. Extremely *comfortable* obnoxious reciprocity...

[[ASIN:B0001FTVDQ Sennheiser HD555 Professional Headphones with Sound Channeling]]sadly, and obnoxious co-workers will continue to be battled with reciprocal obnoxious volume-raising. Extremely *comfortable* obnoxious reciprocity... [[ASIN:B0001FTVDQ Sennheiser HD555 Professional Headphones with Sound Channeling]]
